# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: cooper-union
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] The exterior is largely made of marble, and each elevation of the facade is divided vertically into multiple bays.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] Although the main entrance is on Leonard Street, the western and eastern ends also contain entrances and are clad with rusticated stone blocks.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] On the upper stories, band courses run horizontally across the facade, and there are arched and rectangular windows.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] Along Broadway, above the 12th story, is an ornate clock tower, with a mechanically wound clock.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] A two-story penthouse is placed above the original roof.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] Inside the building are 152 condominium residences.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] The entrances lead to various lobbies, stairs, and hallways, some of which are elaborately decorated.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] In addition, there is a banquet hall within a former banking room near Lafayette Street; former executive offices on the lower floors; and residential amenities in the cellar and on the roof.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] The present building at 346 Broadway was constructed in two phases, replacing a previous structure built in 1870.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] The eastern section was completed in 1896 as an annex of the previous building, while the western section was built in 1898 to replace the older building entirely.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] New York Life occupied the rebuilt edifice for three decades, moving to 51 Madison Avenue in 1928, although the firm continued to own the building until 1945.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] Clothing firms also rented space in the building during the early 20th century, and 346 Broadway hosted various U.S. federal and New York state government offices from the 1930s to the 1960s.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] After the government of New York City acquired the building in 1967, the structure housed the Summons Court and other judicial functions, as well as an art gallery.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] The Peebles Corporation and El-Ad Group bought the building for $160 million in 2013 and renovated it for residential use.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] Following various legal issues, the first condominiums in the building were sold in March 2018.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] 108 Leonard is in the Tribeca neighborhood of Lower Manhattan in New York City, at 346 Broadway.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] It occupies a city block bounded by Broadway to the west, Leonard Street to the north, Lafayette Street to the east, and Catherine Lane to the south.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] The land lot is trapezoidal and covers 28,566 ft2 (2,650 m2).
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] The site is long and narrow, measuring about 400 ft (120 m) wide on both Leonard Street to the north and Catherine Lane to the south.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] However, it only measures 60 ft (18 m) wide on Broadway and about 83 ft (25 m) wide on Lafayette Street.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] There are vaults under the sidewalk on Broadway, Catherine Lane, and Leonard Street.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] Nearby sites include 319 Broadway to the southwest; 33 Thomas Street to the west; 359 Broadway and 361 Broadway to the northwest; and the Jacob K.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] Prior to the development of the current building, the site had been occupied by the Appleton Building, designed by Frederic Diaper and built from 1838 to 1840.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] The building housed the New York Society Library until 1856, when publishing firm D.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] Appleton & Company moved into the space.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] Appleton structure burned down in 1867 and was replaced with the first New York Life building on the site, designed by Griffith Thomas and completed in 1870.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] Until 1894, the site also contained a firehouse for Engine 31 of the New York City Fire Department, at 116 Leonard Street, as well as the clubhouse of the Merchant's Club at 108 Leonard Street.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] 108 Leonard was constructed as the New York Life Building and was finished in two phases.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] The eastern part of the building was built from 1894 to 1896 and was initially designed by Stephen Decatur Hatch, who died midway during construction.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] McKim, Mead & White oversaw the completion of the eastern section.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] The western part of the building, including a three-story clock tower, was constructed from 1896 to 1898 and was designed solely by McKim, Mead & White.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] 108 Leonard occupies its entire block and has a narrow massing.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] The site slopes downward from west to east, so the building is 12 stories tall at its western end and 13 stories tall at its eastern end.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] Including the clock tower, the building has 15 physical above-ground stories; the top three stories are within the clock tower.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] There are also two below-ground levels: a basement is at the same height as the ground on Lafayette Street, as well as a cellar completely below ground.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] Mezzanines above the cellar and the 12th story are excluded from the floor count.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] A two-story penthouse structure was constructed above the 12th story (labeled as floor 14) in the 2010s.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] The penthouse contains setbacks at both its lower and upper levels.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] The top of the clock tower is physically equivalent to the 17th story, while the primary roof is 210 ft (64 m) above ground.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] The basement through 17th story are numbered as floors 1 through 19, respectively; floor number 13 is skipped.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] 108 Leonard's facade is largely made of white Tuckahoe marble, except the southern elevation, which is made of brick and terracotta.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] The facade is divided vertically into 26 bays to the north and south, three bays to the west, and five bays to the east.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] The northern and southern elevations are flanked by end pavilions measuring three bays wide, and there is also a four-bay-wide entrance pavilion at the center of the northern elevation.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] There are three residential entrances, one each on Broadway, Leonard Street, and Lafayette Street.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] In addition, there is an entrance on Broadway leading to retail space; an entrance on Leonard Street, leading to a community facility and banking hall; a garage door on Leonard Street; and three service entrances on Catherine Lane.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] The exterior walls are made of marble, granite, terracotta, and brick, while the windows are generally made of glass and aluminum.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] Surrounding the entire building at the 13th story (floor 15) are stone parapets, which are decorated with openwork motifs of interlocking circles.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] In addition, floors 16 and 17 are surrounded by glass-and-aluminum parapets.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] The western end of 108 Leonard comprises a pavilion measuring three bays wide on Broadway, Catherine Lane, and Leonard Street.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] All three elevations of this pavilion are clad with rusticated blocks of marble.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] The main entrance on Broadway is designed to resemble a portico, with double-height pilasters and freestanding columns topped by an entablature with a balustrade.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] The portico originally contained six freestanding columns that projected from the facade, but these were removed in 1912 at the request of the government of New York City.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] Each of the polished-granite pillars weighed over 16 short tons (14 long tons; 15 t) and measured 23 ft (7.0 m) long by 3 ft (0.91 m) across.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] The capitals of each column are decorated with rosettes and swags in a modified Ionic order.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] Recessed within this main entrance is a double-height curved vestibule, which includes two archways with acanthus and scallop decorations.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] The archways themselves contain cast-bronze window frames above the doors, while the vestibule's ceiling contains a coffered ceiling with an eagle motif at the center.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] On either side of the entrance are panels with acanthus motifs.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] The third story contains round-arched windows, separated by lions' heads and garlands; the corners are decorated with cartouches.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] A cornice with modillions runs above the 3rd story, above which is a bronze railing.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] Band courses run horizontally across the facade above the 4th, 6th, 7th, 9th, and 10th stories, thereby dividing the facade into alternating sections of one and two stories.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] In addition, the windows on the 7th and 10th stories are flanked by panels with acanthus-leaf motifs.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] At the 11th and 12th stories, the window openings are composed of double-height arches.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] Above this is a deep cornice with modillions.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] The attic is surrounded by a balustrade with stone eagles at each of its corners, which represent New York Life.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] This balustrade supports a clock tower that rises another two stories above the main roof (see 108 Leonard § Clock tower).
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] The eastern end of 108 Leonard comprises a pavilion measuring five bays wide on Lafayette Street and four bays wide on Catherine Lane and Leonard Street.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] On the eastern elevation, the center bay projects slightly from the facade.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] At ground level (actually the basement), there is a low archway with two columns on either side.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] The center windows on the 1st and 2nd stories contain colonnettes, which divide the archways there into three segments.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] The other bays each contain one round-arched window on the 1st story and one square-headed window on the 2nd story.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] There are two windows per bay in the remaining stories; the windows on the 3rd, 4th, 10th, and 12th stories are round-arched, while the other windows are square-headed.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] Band courses and cornices run horizontally across this pavilion above each of the first four stories and above the 6th, 7th, 9th, and 10th stories.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] As in the Broadway pavilion, there are relief panels between the windows on the 7th and 10th stories.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] The parapet above the 12th story contains a clock tower with one face, which measures 12 ft (3.7 m) across.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] The dome of this tower contains a copper roof.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] For the most part, the Leonard Street and Catherine Lane elevations are divided into bays with two windows per story.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] At the center of the Leonard Street elevation, there is a three-bay-wide entrance pavilion that projects slightly from the facade.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] At ground level (actually the basement), the main entrance is through a double-height round arch.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] The doors in this arch are topped by spandrel panels with foliate patterns.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] The main entrance is flanked by two pairs of two single-story pilasters, one stacked above the other.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] The bays on each side of the doorways contain round-arched openings.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] Above the basement, the central bay of the entrance pavilion contains three windows per story, while the other bays contain two windows.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] The windows on the upper stories are largely similar in design to those on the rest of the facade.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] The remainder of the Leonard Street elevation is divided by band courses at the same levels as on the Lafayette Street pavilion.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] There are nine bays to the west of the entrance pavilion, excluding the Broadway pavilion.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] In the western bays, the 1st and 2nd stories contain square-headed windows with composite columns between them.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] There are seven such bays to the east of the entrance pavilion, excluding the Lafayette Street pavilion.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] These bays contain double-height archways on the 1st and 2nd stories, since these originally overlooked the general office.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] The windows on the other stories are separated by flat pilasters; the windows on the 3rd, 4th, 10th, and 12th stories are round-arched, while the other windows are square-headed.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] Above the 12th story is a balustrade with a parapet.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] The Catherine Lane elevation is mostly clad in gray brick and terracotta, with the exception of the three westernmost and four easternmost bays, which are respectively part of the Broadway and Lafayette Street pavilions.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] There are two rectangular windows in each bay, except in the end pavilions.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] As with the Leonard Street elevation, the central three bays project from the facade.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] There are nine bays to the west and seven bays to the east, excluding the pavilions on either end.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] The 11th and 12th stories contain round-arched windows above a cornice with modillions.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] The roofs contain insulating membranes, which are covered with pavers.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] There are five skylights on the roof, above unit 14A; the original skylights above the building's emergency stair have been sealed.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] The primary roof above floor 16 contains dormer structures for elevators, stairs, and mechanical equipment.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] Above the 12th story, on the Broadway side of the building, is a clock manufactured by the E.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] The base of the clock tower is two stories tall, while the clock tower itself rises another three stories.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] The clock has four faces, each measuring 12 ft (3.7 m) in diameter and marked with Roman numerals.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] Each corner of the clock tower was ornamented by a 20-foot-tall column.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] The clock tower was topped with by a 33 ft-tall (10 m), 8-short-ton (7.1-long-ton; 7.3 t) sculpture made by French-American sculptor Philip Martiny.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] The piece consisted of four 11 ft-tall (3.4 m) crouching figures of Atlas, which supported a hollow globe measuring 15 feet wide.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] A solid sphere measuring 8 ft (2.4 m) wide was placed within the globe to give the impression of solidity.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] The globe was topped by a 7 ft-tall (2.1 m) eagle.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] The gigantic statue was removed sometime after 1928 and has been lost ever since.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] Inside the clock tower, on the 13th story (labeled as floor 17), is a double-height rectangular room with brick walls, four windows, and exposed ceiling beams.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] A doorway leads from the room to an outdoor terrace.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] From the 1970s until 2013, this space was occupied by the 10,000 ft2 (930 m2) Clocktower Gallery.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] A metal spiral staircase leads up to the clock's machine room, which is physically on the 15th floor.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] The machine room is surrounded by the clock's four faces.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] The machinery in the machine room includes a 1,000 lb (450 kg) weight, which descends to strike a 5,000 lb (2,300 kg) bell.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] The bell was made by the McShane Bell Foundry.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] A hammer, powered by a pair of 800 lb (360 kg) weights, strikes the bell at every hour.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] The clock was wound using a small hand crank, and it had to be re-wound every seven days.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] Until the 2010s, this was one of a few remaining mechanically wound clocks in New York City.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] As of 2023, the clock was not operational.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] The original building's structural frame consists of steel beams, which are spanned by flat arches made of terracotta and are covered with a layer of concrete.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] The western section of the original building is supported by built-up groups of columns, while the eastern section contains circular and rectangular cast iron columns.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] The penthouse contains floor slabs and columns made of cast-in-place concrete.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] The basement could accommodate a live load of up to 100 pounds per square foot (4.8 kilopascals), while the upper stories could accommodate live loads of 75 psf (3.6 kPa).
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] In addition, the stairs, elevator lobbies, public areas, and mechanical areas of the penthouses can accommodate up to 100 psf (4.8 kPa), while the apartments in the penthouses can hold up to 40 psf (1.9 kPa).
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] When the New York Life Building was constructed, each story was laid out around a passageway that ran from west to east, and the office (later residential) space was clustered north and south of this passageway.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] There are equipment rooms on the cellar, on floor 14, and on the roof above the penthouse (labeled as floor 16).
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] The Leonard Street entrance leads to a double-height main lobby.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] The space is designated as a New York City interior landmark and contains a terrazzo floor and marble walls.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] The north wall of the lobby, on either side of the doorway, contains motifs of triple garlands.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] The lobby is surrounded by a band with a Greek key motif, placed about halfway up the wall.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] Above this band, on the eastern and western walls, are two Ionic pilasters, which in turn support a cornice that is decorated with rosettes.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] These pilasters divide the walls into three panels, each with a bronze frame and bronze centerpiece.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] The lobby is flanked by a pair of staircases, which rise to the first story (labeled as floor 2).
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] These staircases contain marble balustrades, as well as newel posts with bronze globes at the top and bottom of each stair.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] There is also a bronze chandelier hanging from the center from the ceiling.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] In the 2010s, the floors were renovated with wooden planks laid in a chevron pattern.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] The modern-day residential building has two additional lobbies, in addition to the landmarked main lobby.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] The basement and first story of the main lobby lead to two semicircular elevator banks of similar design.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] The lower level leads to a semicircular hall that connects with seven elevator cabs, as well as a doorway at the center, flanked by half-columns and pilasters.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] The coffered ceiling contains lanterns, which hang from rosettes and illuminate the space in front of each elevator door.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] The upper level is similar, except that the ceiling has a floral molding instead.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] Hatch's initial plan for a circular stairway, connecting each floor near the center of the elevator lobby, was scrapped when McKim, Mead & White took over the design.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] The elevators were removed in the 2010s, and the elevator doors were replaced with grilles.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] Three new elevator cores (each with two passenger elevators), as well as a service elevator stopping at all stories, were installed during the 2010s renovation.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] 108 Leonard contains six emergency exit stairs, one of which is an official New York City landmark.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] The landmark-protected stairway is made of stone and cast-iron.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] It is to the west of the elevator hall, rising to the 14th story.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] The staircase contains marble steps, classical decorations, and a metal railing decorated with acanthus and Greek key designs.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] The walls of the stairway contain marble paneling on the lowest two stories, while those on the other stories are decorated with marble dadoes.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] The former New York Life banking room, known as the general office, is on the east side of the building, occupying the first and second stories (floors 2 and 3) next to the lobby.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] The double-height space measures three bays from north to south and six bays from east to west.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] The general office contains double-height windows facing north and south, as well as freestanding Corinthian-style columns that are arranged into two groups.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] Tellers' cages, with screens at their tops, were arranged around the room.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] The ceiling is painted and contains gilded octagonal coffers, which in turn are separated by a grid of molded bands.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] The south wall contains a marble safe, which was originally freestanding.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] The west and east walls each contain three arches.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] The central arches on either side lead to the hallways on floor 3, and the two outer archways on the eastern wall contains bulls-eye windows.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] The balcony at floor 3 was part of Hatch's original plan but was removed from McKim, Mead & White's final design; it was added in a later renovation.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] In the 2010s, the banking room was converted into a banquet hall.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] An elevator connects both levels of the banking hall.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] East of the banking room, a narrow flight of stairs leads up from floor 2.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] The staircase contains a decorative metal railing and leads to floor 3 and the general office's balcony.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] The hallway on floor 3 contains plaster walls; rectangular doorways with console brackets; a plaster ceiling with panels; and a classically inspired cornice.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] The ceiling of the hallway includes a plaster relief with New York Life's monogram, as well as caduceus motifs.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] There are similar hallways on the upper floors, which contain floors and wainscoting made of marble, as well as metal decorations.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] The hallway on floor 3 leads to a group of rooms that originally served as executive offices; Hatch may have designed these rooms.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] These offices were originally decorated with wooden moldings, a pair of fireplace mantels with garlands, and neoclassical doorways, but these were subsequently modified with linoleum floors and fluorescent lights.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] The ceilings of these rooms contain caduceus motifs and monograms, similar to those in the hallway, while the windows are deeply recessed and rise from the floor.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] The south wall of the former committee room included an elliptical arch with a tripartite window.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] The space occupied by these rooms was converted to residential units 3N and 3P in the 2010s.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] Floor 3 originally had a room for New York Life's board of directors, which was decorated by Maitland Armstrong.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] The room was relocated to 51 Madison Avenue in 1928.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] On the fourth story (floor 5), above the eastern end of the building, was a president's suite designed by McKim, Mead & White.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] The president's suite had an anteroom with marble paneling, as well as Ionic pilasters that flanked beige-and-black panels on the walls.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] The anteroom had six doorways, each of which had a marble floor and wooden doors with etched-glass panels.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] The paneled ceiling was decorated with rosettes and was surrounded by a molding with a doubled Greek-key motif.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] This room has also been modified with linoleum floors and fluorescent lights.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] The president's office itself was a rectangular space, with rectangular windows to the east and round-arched windows to the north.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] The walls were decorated with a dado, Ionic pilasters, and a cornice all made of mahogany.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] The plaster ceiling had three oval panels and was surrounded by garlands, a Greek key motif, and rosettes.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] As part of a 2010s renovation, these decorations were relocated to the first story, and the presidents' room was used as a private anteroom for residents.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] The space occupied by the president's office was converted to residential units 5N and 5P in the 2010s.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] On the eastern half of the 11th and 12th stories (floors 12 and 14) were the quarters of the Merchants' Club, also designed by Armstrong.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] The lower story of the club contained a hallway measuring 100 by 15 ft (30.5 by 4.6 m) across and 30 ft (9.1 m) high.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] It was decorated with Greek mosaic tiles; a marble wainscoting topped by a light-brown fresco; and a multicolored ceiling.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] At the far end of the hall was an archway trimmed in brown marble and mahogany, which led to a main dining room.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] On the right (south) side of the hallway was a reception room; a smoking and reading room; and an office and a cashier's room.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] All were decorated in leather and contained mahogany furnishings.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] On the left (north) side of the hallway was a main dining room, decorated in a similar style to the other club rooms.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] A kitchen and some offices were located on the upper story.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] In the 2010s, the office space was converted to condominiums with between one and four bedrooms.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] The building has 152 condominiums, which span floors 2 through 16.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] The clock tower contains a three-story, 6,252-square-foot (580.8 m2) penthouse apartment with five bedrooms and three terraces.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] Four of the units (PH West, 15A, PH North, and PH East) contain private elevators.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] Each unit's ceilings range from 9 to 14 ft (2.7 to 4.3 m) high; on the three highest stories, the apartments have ceilings measuring up to 15 ft (4.6 m) high.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] The apartments also have "gallery walls", which can display art, as well as kitchens and bathrooms with marble.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] The building's condominiums contain wooden floors with oak planks laid in a chevron pattern, and some of the condos contain exterior terraces.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] There are fireplaces in two of the apartments on floor 3 (within the former executive offices), as well as in 11 penthouse apartments.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] The northeastern corner of floor 5, which was also designated as a New York City interior landmark, was adapted into a three-bedroom apartment.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] 108 Leonard contains a 20,000-square-foot (1,900 m2) amenity space for residents, such as a swimming pool, fitness center, roof deck, and wine cellar.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] The swimming pool in the cellar measures 75 by 12 ft (22.9 by 3.7 m) across; next to it are a hot tub, steam room, and men's and women's locker rooms.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] The cellar also includes a fitness center, a children's playroom, and a residents' lounge with sitting and pantry areas.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] The building has two bicycle-storage rooms, with a combined capacity of 76 bikes, as well as two package rooms, one each at the residential lobbies on Leonard Street and Broadway.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] Underneath the Leonard Street sidewalk are vaults at cellar level, which contain 30 private storage bins for residents.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] There is also a parking lot within a portion of the basement.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] The parking lot includes 29 parking spaces (26 for residents and three for visitors), as well as an access driveway from Leonard Street, which doubles as a heated motor court.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] A private deck for residents is located at floors 16 and 17, above the lower and upper levels of the penthouse, respectively.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] The New York Life Insurance Company had been chartered in 1841 and was originally located in the Financial District of Lower Manhattan.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] The firm was originally known as the Nautilus Insurance Company, but it assumed the New York Life name in 1849.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] Its previous structures in New York City had been clustered around Lower Manhattan.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] By the late 19th century, life insurance companies generally had their own buildings for their offices and branch locations.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] According to architectural writer Kenneth Gibbs, these buildings allowed each individual company to instill "not only its name but also a favorable impression of its operations" in the general public.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] This had been a trend since 1870, when the Equitable Life Insurance Company completed the first Equitable Life Building in Manhattan's Financial District.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] Furthermore, life insurance companies of the late 19th and early 20th centuries generally built massive buildings to fit their large clerical and records-keeping staff.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] After plans for the Equitable Life Building were announced, New York Life devised plans for its own headquarters in Lower Manhattan.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] In 1868, the company selected a site at 346 Broadway, which had formerly contained publishing firm D.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] Following an architectural design competition in late 1867, New York Life had hired architect Griffith Thomas to design its new edifice.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] The structure is variously described as having been built in the Second Empire style or the Italianate style.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] New York Life and Equitable Life competed to develop their respective headquarters; the two firms' structures even opened on the same day, May 1, 1870.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] The two designs inspired those of other insurance buildings nearby, including the headquarters of Mutual Life, Metropolitan Life, and Germania Life.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] The 85 ft-high (26 m) building, with four stories and a raised basement, occupied the western half of the block.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] The site was irregularly shaped, with a frontage of about 200 ft (61 m) on Leonard Street and Catherine Lane.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] Its marble facade included Ionic columns in a manner resembling the Erechtheion in Athens, as well as heavy plate-glass windows.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] The basement had brick-and-stone walls; the site sloped downward to the east, where the basement contained storefronts.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] The central portion of the building was three stories high (excluding the basement) and was flanked by four-story pavilions at either end.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] The main entrance on Broadway was through a portico, topped by a pediment with an eagle.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] Running west-east across the first floor was a 12 ft-wide (3.7 m) hallway, which was flanked by two large rooms and connected to a stair with an elevator shaft.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] The old New York Life Building was one of the first buildings in New York City with an elevator.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] After the building opened, Henry Fernbach designed a mansard roof, which was completed in 1879.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] New York Life gradually purchased the lots on the eastern portion of the block, extending east to Lafayette Street (then known as Elm Street).
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] By the early 1890s, New York Life had acquired all buildings on the eastern portion of the block.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] New York Life decided to host a closed design competition, hiring five architects and firms (Stephen Decatur Hatch, McKim, Mead & White, George B.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] Post, Babb, Cook & Willard, and Daniel Burnham) to design an annex to the existing building.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] This annex would be a 12-story structure faced with marble, except on Catherine Lane, where the facade would be made of brick.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] Each of the competitors would receive $500 for participating.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] New York Life had prioritized "the largest possible income...consistent with proper light and air" extending east to Lafayette Street (then known as Elm Street).
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] Architects at the time were typically paid a 5 percent commission, but New York Life was reluctant to pay such a high commission.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] Four of the five competitors agreed not to receive less than a 5 percent commission, but Hatch was content with a 3.5 percent commission.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] The company decided in August 1893 to hire Hatch, who was less well-known than the other competitors, to design the annex.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] Plans for the annex were filed in April 1894.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] The project would also involve masonry contractor L.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] Armstrong, marble contractor Norcross Company, iron contractor Post and McCord, and carpenter E.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] Construction commenced in May 1894, but Hatch died three months later, before construction was completed.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] After Hatch's death, McKim, Mead & White took over the project, designing an annex that extended about 200 ft (61 m) west from Elm Street.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] The annex ultimately cost $1.5 million to construct.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] The Merchant's Club moved into the top two stories of the annex, which opened in February 1896.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] The *New-York Tribune* wrote that the structure would be "one of the most striking improvements in Broadway" south of Canal Street.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] *The New York Times* described the New York Life Building as being in a "rivalry" with the Central National Bank Building to the south, at Pearl Street and Broadway.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] During the construction of the annex, New York Life decided to replace the original building as well.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] Although the white-marble facade, cornices, arched windows, and the proportions of the annex harmonized with that of the original building, New York Life officials felt the juxtaposition of the original building and annex "would not be an aesthetic success".
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] M cKim, Mead & White designed the replacement in the Italian Renaissance Revival style.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] The replacement structure and its clock tower were designed by Henry Bacon of McKim, Mead & White, under the supervision of William Rutherford Mead.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] In December 1895, McKim, Mead & White filed plans for the structure at a projected cost of $1 million.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] During the replacement building's construction, falling masonry injured two workers in 1896, and an elevator collapsed and injured six workers in 1897.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] As part of the project, New York Life wanted to take over Catherine Lane and build vaults underneath it; this was difficult because the alley was city-owned property.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] In addition, New York Life wanted to build an entrance portico on Broadway, but New York City's commissioner of public works had initially forbidden the portico's construction.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] New York Life was eventually allowed to build a projecting portico with six columns and an ornate balustrade.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] The Merchants' Association moved into the ground floor of the structure in July 1897.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] McKim, Mead & White completed the replacement building in April 1898.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] New York Life occupied the rebuilt edifice for three decades after the expansions were completed, and the structure became known as the "Temple of Humanity".
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] In the early 1900s, tenants included law firm Sullivan, Goldsmith & Engel; numbering-machine manufacturer Bates Machine Company; and bank Trust Company of the Republic.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] New York Life bought an adjacent site in 1904, intending to construct a quarters for the company's growing clerical staff.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] Afterward, the company rented out the newly vacated space at 346 Broadway.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] Ten people were hurt in 1911 when an elevator in the building fell down eight stories.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] The next year, the portico in front of the building's Broadway entrance was removed.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] By the late 1910s, the surrounding area had become a hub for fashion and textile companies.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] At the time, four stories in the New York Life Building were devoted exclusively to hosiery and underwear firms.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] During the 1920s, New York Life underwent another period of rapid growth, and the company's operations could no longer fit in the 346 Broadway building.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] As a result, New York Life decided to expand into the upper floors, which were occupied by knitted-goods firms; all the knitted-goods tenants decided to relocate across Broadway simultaneously.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] Even this was not enough for New York Life, which in 1924 announced plans to build a skyscraper uptown at 51 Madison Avenue, on the site of Madison Square Garden.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] A one-foot-square piece of masonry fell from 346 Broadway in 1927, although no one was hurt.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] On November 15, 1928, New York Life transferred 75 million documents representing $6.85 billion in policies to the new building.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] An additional $675 million in securities was transported to the new structure, protected by 100 armored cars with machine guns.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] After New York Life vacated 346 Broadway, the building started to attract clothing firms.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] Smith & Son, which had been one of the building's first tenants but had moved out during the 1910s.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] The building's tenants included three outerwear producers at the end of 1930, and the Charles F.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] Noyes Company took over as the building's leasing agent the same year.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] Several city government agencies then leased space in the building, including the Department of Water Supply (which leased the basement, 11th, and 12th floors); the Department of Public Welfare; and the Department of Finance's Emergency Revenue division.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] Other tenants around this time included the Veterans Voters League.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] When the New York state government's Mortgage Commission Servicing Corporation leased four floors in 1935, the structure was renamed the Mortgage Commission Servicing Corporation Building.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] The corporation moved into the building that December and leased two more stories shortly afterward, occupying half of the structure.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] The building was fully occupied in the early 1940s.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] The New York branch of the federal government's Veterans Administration moved into 346 Broadway in 1942, leasing four floors with an option for four more.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] The VA expanded its space the next year, and it occupied the entirety of 346 Broadway and the neighboring 350 Broadway by 1944.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] New York Life sold the building in August 1945 to the City Investing Company, led by Robert Dowling.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] The building was renovated around 1947, when steam pipes and electric elevators were installed.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] Noyes and the City Investing Company each owned a 50 percent stake in the building until 1948, when Noyes gave his ownership stake to the Jessie Smith Noyes Foundation to fund scholarships for college students.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] The East New York Savings Bank placed a $1 million mortgage loan on the building in 1951.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] The VA office in the building was transferred to Philadelphia the same year.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] The City Investing Company sold 346 Broadway to New York Equities, a syndicate led by David Rapoport, at the beginning of 1952.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] At the time, the building was valued at $1 million, while the land was worth an additional $1.6 million.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] During this decade, tenants included the Office of Price Stabilization, as well as recruitment offices for the United States Navy and the United States Marine Corps.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] In addition, the United States Agency for International Development opened a recruitment office in the main lobby in 1967.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] In 1967, the New York City government acquired the building and moved several city agencies there.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] The city's Summons Court, which itself was nicknamed "346", moved into the building.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] 346 Broadway also hosted some Criminal Court cases during the early 1970s, as well as the Criminal Court's Summons Part office, where residents could file complaints about incidents where the New York City Police Department declined to make an arrest.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] The first alternative dispute resolution center in New York City opened within the building in 1975.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] The Clocktower art gallery, operated by the Institute for Art and Urban Resources, had opened by 1973; it occupied an underused space on the 13th floor.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] The Summons Court was handling one hundred thousand cases annually by the late 1970s.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] Meanwhile, the building had become dilapidated; *The New York Times* wrote that "the rooms at 346 have not been painted in at least a dozen years, dirt on the windows blocks out the sun and more than half the light fixtures have broken bulbs".
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] The Criminal Court Summons Part was relocated from the building in 1979, at which point between 2.5 million and 3 million summonses were stored in cabinets and drawers across the building.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] City employees Marvin Schneider and Eric Reiner restored 346 Broadway's clock in 1980.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] The city government would not let Schneider and Reiner fix the clock without liability insurance, so New York Life donated an insurance policy for the two men.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] Schneider had never fixed a clock before, but he thought 346 Broadway's broken clock signified "a city that wasn't working".
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] After fixing the clock, Schneider, Reiner, and George Whaley were asked to fix clocks in other city buildings, and they continued to wind 346 Broadway's clock every week.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] In addition, Schneider began petitioning the New York City Landmarks Preservation Commission (LPC) to designate the former New York Life Building as a city landmark.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] The building was added to the National Register of Historic Places in 1982.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] In part due to Schneider's advocacy, the LPC designated the building's exterior and parts of the interior as a landmark on February 12, 1987; the interior-landmark designation covered ten separate parts of the building.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] City officials and former Rikers Island prisoners built five courtrooms in the building during the 1980s; the new courtrooms did not include prisoner holding cells, so they were used for Civil Court cases instead of criminal cases.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] By 1993, the Department of Citywide Administrative Services had restored the ninth floor for the probation department.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] The old New York Life Building continued to physically deteriorate through the 1990s, as many of the interior spaces had been covered with linoleum, divided by partitions, and marked by graffiti.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] The city's general services commissioner, William J.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] Diamond, said that 346 Broadway was one of the few city-owned buildings that could be feasibly converted into a private development.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] The interior spaces continued to be publicly accessible in the 2000s, although the clock tower was only accessible on Wednesdays.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] The probation department and summons court remained at the building until the early 2010s.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] The Peebles Corporation, along with its partner El-Ad Group, bought the former New York Life Building from the city for $160 million in 2013; this was part of a $250 million deal that also involved the sale of 49 Chambers to the Chetrit Group.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] The New York City government sold the buildings in an attempt to reduce the amount of office space that it owned.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] Peebles finalized its acquisition in December 2013; it was the most expensive property to be sold by the New York City government.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] 346 Broadway was Peebles's first property in New York City.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] The Clocktower Gallery closed that year.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] Immediately after buying the building, Peebles and El-Ad announced they would convert the building into luxury residences.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] As part of the project, the building would contain either 130 or 140 residences.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] Beyer of architectural firm Beyer Blinder Belle proposed relocating the building's staircases, adding two penthouses, and removing fire escapes to make way for private balconies.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] The developers planned to convert the publicly accessible clock tower into a private residence, and they wished to replace the clock's mechanical workings with electric machinery; the developers shut off electricity to the clock in May 2014.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] The building was originally supposed to contain a hotel, plans for which had been scrapped by July 2014.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] The development also had to include a 16,000 ft2 (1,500 m2) community space; by October 2014, local residents were expressing concerns that the developers were trying to downsize the community space.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] The LPC voted in December 2014 to grant a "certificate of appropriateness" to the clock tower's conversion, despite public opposition to that part of the project.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] Schneider continued to visit the building every week to wind the clock until March 2015, when the developers stopped granting him access to the clock tower.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] Negotiations over aspects of the design continued for several months.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] The city had temporarily leased back some space for the summons court and probation department, but the lease ran only until October 2015.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] Initially, the city government had intended to relocate the summons court to another building in Tribeca, prompting a lawsuit from local residents and organizations.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] The probation department relocated from 346 Broadway to the Financial District in January 2014, despite local opposition to that move.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] The city eventually dropped its original plan to relocate the summons court within Tribeca, and the court remained at 346 Broadway for another year, delaying the residential conversion project.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] The summons court ultimately moved to the Municipal Building in early 2015.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] The developers also faced several legal challenges.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] In late 2015, minority developer Dan Hoeg sued Peebles, claiming that the firm had refused to give him 25 percent of the project's profit as part of an agreement with Peebles.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] Peebles denied that Hoeg had any equity stake in the building, and he countersued the next year. former Peebles executive Daniel Newhouse had also sued Peebles for a stake in 346 Broadway's profits, but Newhouse withdrew his suit in 2015.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] Preservationists sued in the New York Supreme Court, the trial-level court of New York state, to prevent the conversion of the clock tower into a private residence.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] The Supreme Court revoked the LPC's certificate of appropriateness in March 2016, despite the city government's own assertion that the building's owners did not have to maintain the clock.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] Peebles and El-Ad also had an issue with an appraiser when Peebles sought to have El-Ad buy out his stake in the project.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] A panel of state judges upheld the Supreme Court's ruling in November 2017.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] Peebles and El-Ad developers also sued each other the same year, accusing each other of trying to derail the project.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] If the developers did not sell at least 35 apartments by August 2018, the city could take back ownership of the building.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] By November 2017, Peebles and El-Ad had resolved their legal disputes.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] Bank of America gave the owners a $334 million construction loan in January 2016, and Apollo Commercial Real Estate Finance placed a $77 million mezzanine loan on the project the next month.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] Zimmerman Architects restored the building's facade.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] The work included cleaning the marble, replacing damaged portions of the roof parapet, and restoring the 7,000-pound sculptural eagles perched on the roof.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] Afterward, Jeffrey Beers International renovated the building's interior.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] A residential entrance was built on Leonard Street, and the building was rebranded as 108 Leonard.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] The building's owners started selling apartments in March 2018, with the cheapest apartments being marketed at $1.5 million.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] Due to the disputes over the clock tower, the developers postponed plans to build a penthouse apartment in the clark tower.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] The New York Court of Appeals, the highest court in New York state, reversed the New York Supreme Court's ruling on the clock-tower lawsuit in early 2019, finding that the owners could close the clock tower and convert it into an apartment.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] The Court of Appeals' ruling effectively ended the legal dispute, to preservationists' disappointment, and the penthouse was placed on sale in 2024.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] Peebles and El-Ad refinanced the building in September 2019 with $450 million from Mack Real Estate Credit Strategies.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] Among the building's early residents were singer Keith Urban and actress Nicole Kidman; singer Sabrina Carpenter; Alexandra Clancy, the widow of writer Tom Clancy; and actor Hugh Jackman.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] The music executive Clive Davis bought an apartment in the building but sold it in 2023 without having lived there.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] In early 2022, JPMorgan Chase and Lionheart Management provided a $229.4 million mortgage loan for the project.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] Jack Shainman, operator of the Jack Shainman Gallery, announced in November 2022 that he would open a 20,000-square-foot (1,900 m2) gallery within 108 Leonard's banking hall in late 2023.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] Shainman had paid $20 million for the banking hall and was planning to spend $3 million to $4 million on renovations.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] The Jack Shainman Gallery soft opened in the building in January 2024.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] That March, VIQ Architecture submitted plans to the LPC for alterations to the banking hall's interior, as well as the lower portions of the facade on Leonard Street and Lafayette Street.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] There was also some criticism of the building.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] The writer Eliot Gregory did not like the decorations atop the clock tower, writing in 1899 that the decorations resembled "a monument in Greenwood (Cemetery), surmounted by a rat trap".
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] When Gray described the rundown building in a *Times* article in 1993, he said that the Leonard Street lobby contained "the tackiest fake-veneer candy stand left in the city, complete with Beirut-style rolldown steel gates".
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] Although general services commissioner Kenneth J.
[src:cooper-union/108-leonard] Knuckles complained about Gray's article, Knuckles also did not dispute any of the details mentioned in the article.
[src:cooper-union/115th-street-library] The **Harry Belafonte 115th Street Branch** of the New York Public Library is a historic library building located in Harlem, New York City.
[src:cooper-union/115th-street-library] It was designed by McKim, Mead & White and built in 1907–1908 and opened on November 6, 1908.
[src:cooper-union/115th-street-library] It is a three-story-high, three-bay-wide building faced in deeply rusticated gray limestone in a Neo Italian Renaissance style.
[src:cooper-union/115th-street-library] The branch was one of 65 built by the New York Public Library with funds provided by the philanthropist Andrew Carnegie, 11 of them designed by McKim, Mead & White.
[src:cooper-union/115th-street-library] The building is 50 feet wide and features three evenly spaced arched openings on the first floor.
[src:cooper-union/115th-street-library] The branch served as Harlem cultural center and hub of organizing efforts.
[src:cooper-union/115th-street-library] It was listed on the National Register of Historic Places in 1980.
[src:cooper-union/115th-street-library] In 2017, the branch was renamed to honor Harry Belafonte who lived near the branch.
[src:cooper-union/115th-street-library] Another branch of the Library, the Schomburg Center holds Belafonte's archives.
[src:cooper-union/116-john-street] It was listed on the National Register of Historic Places in 2014.
[src:cooper-union/116-john-street] Larry Silverstein bought the building in 2021 for $248 million.
[src:cooper-union/116th-street-columbia-university-station] The **116th Street–Columbia University station** is a local station on the IRT Broadway–Seventh Avenue Line of the New York City Subway.
[src:cooper-union/116th-street-columbia-university-station] It is located at the intersection of Broadway and 116th Street in the Morningside Heights neighborhood of Manhattan, just outside the west gate to the main campus of Columbia University and the southeast corner of the Barnard College campus.
[src:cooper-union/116th-street-columbia-university-station] The station is served by the 1 train at all times.
[src:cooper-union/116th-street-columbia-university-station] The 116th Street station was constructed for the Interborough Rapid Transit Company (IRT) as part of the city's first subway line, which was approved in 1900.
[src:cooper-union/116th-street-columbia-university-station] Construction of the line segment that includes 116th Street began on June 18 of the same year.
[src:cooper-union/116th-street-columbia-university-station] The station opened on October 27, 1904, as one of the original 28 stations of the New York City Subway.
[src:cooper-union/116th-street-columbia-university-station] The station's platforms were lengthened in 1948 to accommodate ten-car trains, the station's median entrance was replaced in the 1960s, and the station was renovated in the 2000s.
[src:cooper-union/116th-street-columbia-university-station] The 116th Street station contains two side platforms and three tracks; the center track is not used in regular service.
[src:cooper-union/116th-street-columbia-university-station] The station was built with tile and mosaic decorations.
[src:cooper-union/116th-street-columbia-university-station] The mezzanine above the platforms contains exits to 116th Street and Broadway, and the northbound platform contains an additional exit to 115th Street.
[src:cooper-union/116th-street-columbia-university-station] The original section of the station is a New York City designated landmark and listed on the National Register of Historic Places.
[src:cooper-union/116th-street-columbia-university-station] Planning for a subway line in New York City dates to 1864, but development of what became the city's first subway line did not start until 1894, when the New York State Legislature passed the Rapid Transit Act.
[src:cooper-union/116th-street-columbia-university-station] The subway plans were drawn up by a team of engineers led by William Barclay Parsons, the Rapid Transit Commission's chief engineer.
[src:cooper-union/116th-street-columbia-university-station] It called for a subway line from New York City Hall in lower Manhattan to the Upper West Side, where two branches would lead north into the Bronx.
[src:cooper-union/116th-street-columbia-university-station] A plan was formally adopted in 1897, and all legal conflicts over the route alignment were resolved near the end of 1899.
[src:cooper-union/116th-street-columbia-university-station] The Rapid Transit Construction Company, organized by John B.
[src:cooper-union/116th-street-columbia-university-station] McDonald and funded by August Belmont Jr., signed the initial Contract 1 with the Rapid Transit Commission in February 1900, under which it would construct the subway and maintain a 50-year operating lease from the opening of the line.
[src:cooper-union/116th-street-columbia-university-station] In 1901, the firm of Heins & LaFarge was hired to design the underground stations.
[src:cooper-union/116th-street-columbia-university-station] Belmont incorporated the Interborough Rapid Transit Company (IRT) in April 1902 to operate the subway.
[src:cooper-union/116th-street-columbia-university-station] The 116th Street station was constructed as part of the IRT's West Side Line (now the Broadway–Seventh Avenue Line) from 104th Street to 125th Street, for which construction began on June 18, 1900.
[src:cooper-union/116th-street-columbia-university-station] The section of the West Side Line around this station was originally planned as a two-track line, but in early 1901, was changed to a three-track structure to permit train storage in the center track.
[src:cooper-union/116th-street-columbia-university-station] Construction on the section between 104th Street and 125th Street had already begun prior to the design change, requiring that a portion of the work be undone.
[src:cooper-union/116th-street-columbia-university-station] A third track was added directly north of 96th Street, immediately east of the originally planned two tracks.
[src:cooper-union/116th-street-columbia-university-station] By late 1903, the subway was nearly complete, but the IRT Powerhouse and the system's electrical substations were still under construction, delaying the system's opening.
[src:cooper-union/116th-street-columbia-university-station] As late as October 26, 1904, the day before the subway was scheduled to open, the walls and ceilings were incomplete.
[src:cooper-union/116th-street-columbia-university-station] The 116th Street station opened on October 27, 1904, as one of the original 28 stations of the New York City Subway from City Hall to 145th Street on the West Side Branch.
[src:cooper-union/116th-street-columbia-university-station] The opening of the first subway line, and particularly the 116th Street station, helped contribute to the development of Morningside Heights and Harlem.
[src:cooper-union/116th-street-columbia-university-station] After the first subway line was completed in 1908, the station was served by West Side local and express trains.
[src:cooper-union/116th-street-columbia-university-station] Express trains began at South Ferry in Manhattan or Atlantic Avenue in Brooklyn, and ended at 242nd Street in the Bronx.
[src:cooper-union/116th-street-columbia-university-station] Local trains ran from City Hall to 242nd Street during rush hours, continuing south from City Hall to South Ferry at other times.
[src:cooper-union/116th-street-columbia-university-station] In 1918, the Broadway–Seventh Avenue Line opened south of Times Square–42nd Street, and the original line was divided into an H-shaped system.
[src:cooper-union/116th-street-columbia-university-station] The original subway north of Times Square thus became part of the Broadway–Seventh Avenue Line.
[src:cooper-union/116th-street-columbia-university-station] Local trains were sent to South Ferry, while express trains used the new Clark Street Tunnel to Brooklyn.
[src:cooper-union/116th-street-columbia-university-station] To address overcrowding, in 1909, the New York Public Service Commission proposed lengthening the platforms at stations along the original IRT subway.
[src:cooper-union/116th-street-columbia-university-station] As part of a modification to the IRT's construction contracts made on January 18, 1910, the company was to lengthen station platforms to accommodate ten-car express and six-car local trains.
[src:cooper-union/116th-street-columbia-university-station] In addition to $1.5 million (equivalent to $51.8 million in 2025) spent on platform lengthening, $500,000 (equivalent to $17.3 million in 2025) was spent on building additional entrances and exits.
[src:cooper-union/116th-street-columbia-university-station] It was anticipated that these improvements would increase capacity by 25 percent.
[src:cooper-union/116th-street-columbia-university-station] The northbound platform at the 116th Street station was extended 130 feet (40 m) to the south, while the southbound platform was not lengthened.
[src:cooper-union/116th-street-columbia-university-station] Six-car local trains began operating in October 1910, and ten-car express trains began running on the West Side Line on January 24, 1911.
[src:cooper-union/116th-street-columbia-university-station] Subsequently, the station could accommodate six-car local trains, but ten-car trains could not open some of their doors.
[src:cooper-union/116th-street-columbia-university-station] In conjunction with the platform lengthening, a new entrance was constructed to the northbound platform in 1912.
[src:cooper-union/116th-street-columbia-university-station] An entrance kiosk for the new staircase was taken from the 23rd Street and Fourth Avenue station and was installed in July 1913.
[src:cooper-union/116th-street-columbia-university-station] The city government took over the IRT's operations on June 12, 1940.
[src:cooper-union/116th-street-columbia-university-station] Platforms at IRT Broadway–Seventh Avenue Line stations between 103rd Street and 238th Street, including those at 116th Street, were lengthened to 514 feet (157 m) between 1946 and 1948, allowing full ten-car express trains to stop at these stations.
[src:cooper-union/116th-street-columbia-university-station] A contract for the platform extensions at 116th Street and eight other stations on the line was awarded to Spencer, White & Prentis Inc. in October 1946, with an estimated cost of $3.891 million.
[src:cooper-union/116th-street-columbia-university-station] The platform extensions at these stations were opened in stages.
[src:cooper-union/116th-street-columbia-university-station] On April 6, 1948, the platform extension at 116th Street opened.
[src:cooper-union/116th-street-columbia-university-station] Simultaneously, the IRT routes were given numbered designations with the introduction of "R-type" rolling stock, which contained rollsigns with numbered designations for each service.
[src:cooper-union/116th-street-columbia-university-station] The route to 242nd Street became known as the 1.
[src:cooper-union/116th-street-columbia-university-station] Columbia University first requested the demolition of the station's original entrance in Broadway's median in 1954, ahead of the Columbia University Bicentennial.
[src:cooper-union/116th-street-columbia-university-station] The university brought up the issue again at a meeting of the New York City Board of Estimate in 1963, after a student was killed while crossing the street.
[src:cooper-union/116th-street-columbia-university-station] The kiosk was seen as a safety hazard, with two deaths and several accidents occurring at the kiosk from 1962 to 1964.
[src:cooper-union/116th-street-columbia-university-station] Sixty-eight hundred students and faculty members signed a petition to remove the kiosk in February 1964.
[src:cooper-union/116th-street-columbia-university-station] On March 13, 1964, the New York City Board of Estimate voted to allocate $600,000 (equivalent to $6,228,541 in 2025) to demolish the entrance and replace it with two new sidewalk entrances as part of the 1964–1965 City budget.
[src:cooper-union/116th-street-columbia-university-station] The New York City Department of Highways had requested that funds be allocated to this project at the request of Columbia University.
[src:cooper-union/116th-street-columbia-university-station] The New York City Transit Authority had not yet drawn up plans for the project.
[src:cooper-union/116th-street-columbia-university-station] Bids for the kiosk's demolition were initially scheduled to be solicited in July 1964.
[src:cooper-union/116th-street-columbia-university-station] That October, a NYCTA spokesperson announced that the demolition of the entrance would be delayed until the following spring.
[src:cooper-union/116th-street-columbia-university-station] Work on the project had been expected to commence in December 1964.
[src:cooper-union/116th-street-columbia-university-station] The NYCTA was expected to complete the design of the project in early 1965, after which the project could be put out for bids.
[src:cooper-union/116th-street-columbia-university-station] On November 2, 1966, the New York City Planning Commission voted to grant an additional $300,000 (equivalent to $2,976,923 in 2025) for the project after the cost of the project was revised.
[src:cooper-union/116th-street-columbia-university-station] The money for the project was reallocated within the Highway Department's budget.
[src:cooper-union/116th-street-columbia-university-station] It was estimated that following necessary approvals from the New York City Board of Estimate, bids on the project would be let on December 16, and work on the project would begin by the end of January 1967.
[src:cooper-union/116th-street-columbia-university-station] Work on the project was set to be done in 22 months.
[src:cooper-union/116th-street-columbia-university-station] In 1965, Columbia University and Barnard College had announced that they would each spend $5,000 (equivalent to $51,082 in 2025) to decorate the new entrances to fit in with their campuses.
[src:cooper-union/116th-street-columbia-university-station] Work on the project was completed in 1968.
[src:cooper-union/116th-street-columbia-university-station] In 1979, the New York City Landmarks Preservation Commission designated the space within the boundaries of the original station, excluding expansions made after 1904, as a city landmark.
[src:cooper-union/116th-street-columbia-university-station] The station was designated along with eleven others on the original IRT.
[src:cooper-union/116th-street-columbia-university-station] In April 1988, the NYCTA unveiled plans to speed up service on the Broadway–Seventh Avenue Line through the implementation of a skip-stop service: the 9 train.
[src:cooper-union/116th-street-columbia-university-station] When skip-stop service began on August 21, 1989, it was only implemented north of 137th Street–City College on weekdays, and 116th Street was served by both the 1 and the 9.
[src:cooper-union/116th-street-columbia-university-station] In October 1988, the Metropolitan Transportation Authority (MTA) announced that the newsstand on the station's downtown platform would be removed as part of a citywide program to beautify stations and improve passenger flow.
[src:cooper-union/116th-street-columbia-university-station] The agency began this program in late 1987.
[src:cooper-union/116th-street-columbia-university-station] The owner of the newsstand was unsure of whether he would rebuild the stand as the cost of rebuilding it might have outweighed the benefits of reopening it.
[src:cooper-union/116th-street-columbia-university-station] This newsstand was chosen for rebuilding as it was only 12 feet (3.7 m) away from a staircase.
[src:cooper-union/116th-street-columbia-university-station] In June 2002, the MTA announced that ten subway stations citywide, including 103rd Street, 110th Street, 116th Street, 125th Street, and 231st Street on the IRT Broadway–Seventh Avenue Line, would receive renovations.
[src:cooper-union/116th-street-columbia-university-station] As part of the project, fare control areas would be redesigned, flooring, and electrical and communication systems would be upgraded, and new lighting, public address systems and stairways would be installed.
[src:cooper-union/116th-street-columbia-university-station] In addition, since 110th Street, 116th Street, and 125th Street had landmark status, historical elements would be replaced or restored, including wall tiles.
[src:cooper-union/116th-street-columbia-university-station] At the ends of the station platforms at 103rd Street, 110th Street, and 116th Street, a small section of station wall, which would look identical to the existing station walls, would be added to provide space for scrubber rooms.
[src:cooper-union/116th-street-columbia-university-station] Work on the ten citywide renovation projects was estimated to cost almost $146 million, and was scheduled to start later that year, and be completed in April 2004, in time for the 100th anniversary of the station's opening, and the 250th anniversary of Columbia University.
[src:cooper-union/116th-street-columbia-university-station] Columbia University contributed $1 million (equivalent to $1,750,181 in 2025) to the station renovation project after the MTA said it would have to put off the renovation projects in Manhattan due to funding issues.
[src:cooper-union/116th-street-columbia-university-station] The university had also reached agreements to cover part of the costs of the station renovations at 103rd Street, 110th Street, and 125th Street.
[src:cooper-union/116th-street-columbia-university-station] As a condition of the funding allocation for the station renovation, the university wanted work on the project to be expedited.
[src:cooper-union/116th-street-columbia-university-station] Residents of Morningside Heights approved of the renovation plans, but were concerned that the expedited repairs would come at the cost of damaging the stations' historic elements.
[src:cooper-union/116th-street-columbia-university-station] The MTA was expected to decide whether preservation or speed would be prioritized in the station renovation projects by the end of 2002.
[src:cooper-union/116th-street-columbia-university-station] At the 110th Street and 116th Street stations, local community activists opposed artwork that was planned to be commissioned through the MTA's Arts for Transit program.
[src:cooper-union/116th-street-columbia-university-station] Though the proposed artwork was intended as a homage to the stations' history, the activists believed the art would damage the decorative tiling that dated from the stations' opening, and that the artwork would damage the landmark interiors of the stations.
[src:cooper-union/116th-street-columbia-university-station] The MTA had planned to install a small bronze subway track and train to be inlaid within the station walls surrounded by sepia-toned photographs of the neighborhood at 116th Street.
[src:cooper-union/116th-street-columbia-university-station] In December 2002, Manhattan Community Board 7 voted in favor of the plan to include artwork from the MTA's Arts for Transit program at the 103rd Street station, which was not landmarked.
[src:cooper-union/116th-street-columbia-university-station] Community Board 7 voted against the plan to include new artwork at the landmarked 110th Street and 116th Street stations, and the MTA dropped plans for the artwork at these stations.
[src:cooper-union/116th-street-columbia-university-station] The station renovation project at 116th Street began in January 2003.
[src:cooper-union/116th-street-columbia-university-station] From May 31 to July 12, 2003, the uptown platforms at the 116th Street and 103rd Street stations were closed at all times for their renovations.
[src:cooper-union/116th-street-columbia-university-station] The original interiors were listed on the National Register of Historic Places in 2004.
[src:cooper-union/116th-street-columbia-university-station] Skip-stop service ended on May 27, 2005, as a result of a decrease in the number of riders who benefited.
[src:cooper-union/116th-street-columbia-university-station] This station has two side platforms and three tracks, the center one being an unused express track.
[src:cooper-union/116th-street-columbia-university-station] The station is served by the 1 at all times and is between 125th Street to the north and 110th Street to the south.
[src:cooper-union/116th-street-columbia-university-station] The platforms were originally 350 feet (110 m) long, like at other stations north of 96th Street, but as a result of the 1948 platform extension, became 520 feet (160 m) long.
[src:cooper-union/116th-street-columbia-university-station] The platform extensions are at the southern ends of the original platforms.
[src:cooper-union/116th-street-columbia-university-station] Two staircases from each platform lead to a mezzanine above the platforms, which contains the fare control area.
[src:cooper-union/116th-street-columbia-university-station] Outside fare control, the mezzanine connects to stairways on either side of Broadway.
[src:cooper-union/116th-street-columbia-university-station] The southbound platform contains an artwork by Michelle Greene, *Railrider's Throne*.
[src:cooper-union/116th-street-columbia-university-station] The artwork, installed in 1991 as part of the MTA Arts for Transit program, was originally intended to be temporary.
[src:cooper-union/116th-street-columbia-university-station] Greene said she had created the artwork because she "wanted to create a whimsical environment that allows the commuter to feel special as opposed to alienated".
[src:cooper-union/116th-street-columbia-university-station] The southbound local track is technically known as BB1 while the northbound one is BB4; the BB designation is used for chaining purposes along the Broadway–Seventh Avenue Line from 96th Street to 242nd Street.
[src:cooper-union/116th-street-columbia-university-station] Although it cannot be accessed at 116th Street–Columbia University, the center track is designated as M.
[src:cooper-union/116th-street-columbia-university-station] These designations are rarely, if ever, used in ordinary conversation.
[src:cooper-union/116th-street-columbia-university-station] As with other stations built as part of the original IRT, the station was constructed using a cut-and-cover method.
[src:cooper-union/116th-street-columbia-university-station] The tunnel is covered by a U-shaped trough that contains utility pipes and wires.
[src:cooper-union/116th-street-columbia-university-station] This trough contains a foundation of concrete no less than 4 inches (100 mm) thick.
[src:cooper-union/116th-street-columbia-university-station] Each platform consists of 3-inch-thick (7.6 cm) concrete slabs, beneath which are drainage basins.
[src:cooper-union/116th-street-columbia-university-station] The original platforms contain circular, cast-iron Doric-style columns spaced every 15 feet (4.6 m), while the platform extensions contain I-beam columns.
[src:cooper-union/116th-street-columbia-university-station] Additional columns between the tracks, spaced every 5 feet (1.5 m), support the jack-arched concrete station roofs.
[src:cooper-union/116th-street-columbia-university-station] There is a 1-inch (25 mm) gap between the trough wall and the platform walls, which are made of 4-inch (100 mm)-thick brick covered over by a tiled finish.
[src:cooper-union/116th-street-columbia-university-station] The ceiling is about 8 feet (2.4 m) above platform level in the southern part of the station, but is higher above the northern part, reaching 12 to 15 feet (3.7 to 4.6 m) above the platform.
[src:cooper-union/116th-street-columbia-university-station] The walls along the platforms consist of a buff-colored brick wainscoting on the lowest part of the wall, and white glass tiles above.
[src:cooper-union/116th-street-columbia-university-station] The platform walls are divided at 15-foot (4.6 m) intervals by blue tile pilasters, or vertical bands.
[src:cooper-union/116th-street-columbia-university-station] The pilasters are topped by alternating blue-and-cream faience plaques of the number "116" and the Columbia University seal; both of these motifs are surrounded by faience wreaths.
[src:cooper-union/116th-street-columbia-university-station] The seal shows a seated woman with a book of knowledge in her hand and three children standing near her feet.
[src:cooper-union/116th-street-columbia-university-station] A blue-and-green cornice, made of faience, runs atop the wall and around the mosaic tablets.
[src:cooper-union/116th-street-columbia-university-station] Mosaic wall tablets with the name "Columbia University" are installed along the platform walls.
[src:cooper-union/116th-street-columbia-university-station] The mosaic tiles at all original IRT stations were manufactured by the American Encaustic Tile Company, which subcontracted the installations at each station.
[src:cooper-union/116th-street-columbia-university-station] The decorative work was performed by tile contractor John H.
[src:cooper-union/116th-street-columbia-university-station] Parry and faience contractor Grueby Faience Company.
[src:cooper-union/116th-street-columbia-university-station] The station has four entrance/exit stairs that serve both platforms.
[src:cooper-union/116th-street-columbia-university-station] One pair ascends to the northwest corner of Broadway and 116th Street, while the other pair goes to the northeast corner of the same intersection.
[src:cooper-union/116th-street-columbia-university-station] There is also an exit-only staircase near the southern end of the northbound platform that leads to the east side of Broadway at 115th Street, outside the Alfred Lerner Hall.
[src:cooper-union/116th-street-columbia-university-station] There was a station house in the median of Broadway, just north of 116th Street, which was designed by Heins & LaFarge and dated to the station's opening in 1904.
[src:cooper-union/116th-street-columbia-university-station] It was built as one of several station houses on the original IRT; similar station houses were built at Atlantic Avenue, Bowling Green, Mott Avenue, 72nd Street, and 103rd Street.
[src:cooper-union/116th-street-columbia-university-station] The station house, which was identical to the one at 103rd Street, occupied an area of 50 by 20 feet (15.2 by 6.1 m).
[src:cooper-union/116th-street-columbia-university-station] The one-story station house contained exterior walls made of buff brick, with a foundation made of granite blocks.
[src:cooper-union/116th-street-columbia-university-station] A limestone string course ran atop the exterior wall.
[src:cooper-union/116th-street-columbia-university-station] At the corners of the station house were limestone quoins, which supported a copper-and-terracotta gable roof facing west and east.
[src:cooper-union/116th-street-columbia-university-station] The ridge of the station house's roof was a skylight made of glass and metal.
[src:cooper-union/116th-street-columbia-university-station] The doorways were centrally located on the north and south walls of the control house, topped by terracotta finials and a rounded gable.
[src:cooper-union/116th-street-columbia-university-station] There were terracotta crosses on each rounded gable with the number "116" embossed onto them.
[src:cooper-union/116th-street-columbia-university-station] Above the doorway was a pediment and an arched window made of glass and wrought iron.
[src:cooper-union/116th-street-columbia-university-station] The control house was closed and demolished in 1968.
[src:cooper-union/120-and-122-east-92nd-street] 120 and 122 East 92nd Street are located in the Carnegie Hill section of the Upper East Side of Manhattan in New York City, New York, US.
[src:cooper-union/120-and-122-east-92nd-street] Both houses are among the area's few remaining wooden houses, as wood-frame construction south of 155th Street was banned in 1882.
[src:cooper-union/120-and-122-east-92nd-street] Another wood-frame house is located one block east at 160 East 92nd Street.
[src:cooper-union/120-and-122-east-92nd-street] The houses at 120 and 122 East 92nd Street were described in one source as "reflect[ing] the semi-rural simplicity of another era".
[src:cooper-union/120-and-122-east-92nd-street] Mimi Sheraton of *The New York Times*, visiting the building on the recommendation of the *AIA Guide to New York City*, wrote in 2002 that numbers 120 and 122 were "looking dangerously fragile".
[src:cooper-union/120-and-122-east-92nd-street] 120 East 92nd Street has a brick basement and three stories.
[src:cooper-union/120-and-122-east-92nd-street] An iron railing separates the sidewalk from the front yard.
[src:cooper-union/120-and-122-east-92nd-street] There is a portico in front of the first-floor entrance, reached by a steep wooden staircase.
[src:cooper-union/120-and-122-east-92nd-street] The portico contains openwork columns, behind which are three bays of openings: French windows to the left and center, and a double door with elaborate moldings on the right.
[src:cooper-union/120-and-122-east-92nd-street] On the second and third stories, there are three wood-framed sash windows per floor, which are flanked by shutters.
[src:cooper-union/120-and-122-east-92nd-street] Cornices, decorated with modillions, run above these windows.
[src:cooper-union/120-and-122-east-92nd-street] Inside, many of the original decorative details remain intact, including an entrance vestibule with etched glass, along with an entrance hall with a staircase.
[src:cooper-union/120-and-122-east-92nd-street] The house's first story has a living room with a fireplace, a dining room, a kitchen, and a rear balcony facing the garden.
[src:cooper-union/120-and-122-east-92nd-street] The second floor has a bedroom overlooking the garden, and there is another level with two bedrooms at the top.
[src:cooper-union/120-and-122-east-92nd-street] 122 East 92nd Street, although similar to its neighbor, has a penthouse level recessed above the original roofline.
[src:cooper-union/120-and-122-east-92nd-street] This building may have been designed by Albro Howell, the contractor for both houses.
[src:cooper-union/120-and-122-east-92nd-street] Number 122 has a portico at its first story, which is substantially lower than that of number 120; this portico is accessed by a staircase and contains openwork columns.
[src:cooper-union/120-and-122-east-92nd-street] Behind the porticos are three bays of openings: segmentally arched French doors to the left and center, and a doorway to the right, behind the columns.
[src:cooper-union/120-and-122-east-92nd-street] On the second and third stories, there are three wood-framed sash windows per floor, which are flanked by shutters and have segmentally arched tops.
[src:cooper-union/120-and-122-east-92nd-street] Above the third story is a cornice, with panels interspersed with pairs of brackets.
[src:cooper-union/120-and-122-east-92nd-street] A recessed fourth-story penthouse rises above the roof, and there is another two-story addition extending off the left (eastern) end of the house.
[src:cooper-union/120-and-122-east-92nd-street] Inside, the building retains many of its original decorative details, including an entrance hall with a staircase, along with marble fireplaces.
[src:cooper-union/120-and-122-east-92nd-street] The library is on one of the upper floors, while the kitchen and dining room are in the basement.
[src:cooper-union/120-and-122-east-92nd-street] The penthouse contains a studio, and there is also a garden room extending off the rear of the first story.
[src:cooper-union/120-and-122-east-92nd-street] The building at 122 East 92nd Street was built in 1859 and is the oldest remaining structure on the block of 92nd Street between Park and Lexington avenues.
[src:cooper-union/120-and-122-east-92nd-street] Like other wood-frame residences in the area, the houses were intended for middle-class residents.
[src:cooper-union/120-and-122-east-92nd-street] Number 122 was originally home to a custom house agent, Adam C.
[src:cooper-union/120-and-122-east-92nd-street] Flanagan; he owned it only until 1861, when Hampton D.
[src:cooper-union/120-and-122-east-92nd-street] Its first resident was a wine merchant, John C.
[src:cooper-union/120-and-122-east-92nd-street] Rennert, who had acquired the land from Flanagan.
[src:cooper-union/120-and-122-east-92nd-street] By then, several buildings were being built on neighboring plots, including 121–123 East 92nd Street across the street; further brownstone and masonry buildings were constructed on that block in the 1880s.
[src:cooper-union/120-and-122-east-92nd-street] The Rennert family rented out number 120, and a bathroom was added on the third floor of that property c.
[src:cooper-union/120-and-122-east-92nd-street] Rennert's widow Catherine continued to own 120 East 92nd Street until 1888, when Henrietta Nathan bought it.
[src:cooper-union/120-and-122-east-92nd-street] The cooper Anton Hoffmann bought number 120 in 1890, and his family owned that house for the next seven decades.
[src:cooper-union/120-and-122-east-92nd-street] Number 122, meanwhile, was owned by the stone merchant Henry Hanlein, whose family remained there at least until the 1930s.
[src:cooper-union/120-and-122-east-92nd-street] A penthouse was built above the roof of 122 East 92nd Street in 1927.
[src:cooper-union/120-and-122-east-92nd-street] By the mid-20th century, 120 and 122 East 92nd Street were among the only remaining wood-frame houses on the Upper East Side, along with 160 East 92nd Street and 128 East 93rd Street.
[src:cooper-union/120-and-122-east-92nd-street] Nemone Palestin acquired number 120 in 1958 and renovated it extensively; at the time, that house had faulty mechanical systems and only a single light switch.
[src:cooper-union/120-and-122-east-92nd-street] Palestin rebuilt the interior staircase and walls, and she shored up the back of the house; at the recommendation of Brooklyn Navy Yard personnel, she used an acetylene torch to destroy a tank in the basement.
[src:cooper-union/120-and-122-east-92nd-street] The ground floor and the upper three floors were split into separate units.
[src:cooper-union/120-and-122-east-92nd-street] The New York City Landmarks Preservation Commission (LPC) designated both houses as individual city landmarks in 1969.
[src:cooper-union/120-and-122-east-92nd-street] The houses were not initially listed as part of the LPC's Carnegie Hill Historic District when that district was designated in 1974.
[src:cooper-union/120-and-122-east-92nd-street] When the Carnegie Hill Historic District was expanded in 1993, both structures were included in the expanded district.
[src:cooper-union/120-and-122-east-92nd-street] The houses were added to the National Register of Historic Places in 1982.
[src:cooper-union/120-and-122-east-92nd-street] In 1996, the family of British art historian Anthony Crichton-Stuart bought 120 East 92nd Street; they subsequently renovated the building.
[src:cooper-union/120-and-122-east-92nd-street] By 2005, the Goldrach family—which owned number 122—was repairing the porch, woodwork, and mechanical systems.
[src:cooper-union/120-and-122-east-92nd-street] At the time, the building had fallen into disrepair.
[src:cooper-union/120-and-122-east-92nd-street] Number 120 was also renovated by the Crichton-Stuart family, and by the 2010s it was being leased out.
[src:cooper-union/125th-street-station-irt-broadway-seventh-avenue-line] The **125th Street station** (formerly the **Manhattan Street station**) is an elevated local station on the IRT Broadway–Seventh Avenue Line of the New York City Subway.
[src:cooper-union/125th-street-station-irt-broadway-seventh-avenue-line] Located at the intersection of 125th Street and Broadway, at the border of the Manhattanville and Morningside Heights neighborhoods of Manhattan, it is served by the 1 train at all times.
[src:cooper-union/125th-street-station-irt-broadway-seventh-avenue-line] The 125th Street station was constructed for the Interborough Rapid Transit Company (IRT) as part of the city's first subway line, which was approved in 1900.
[src:cooper-union/125th-street-station-irt-broadway-seventh-avenue-line] Construction of the line segment that includes 125th Street began on June 18 of the same year.
[src:cooper-union/125th-street-station-irt-broadway-seventh-avenue-line] The station's platforms were lengthened in 1948, and the station was renovated in the 2000s.
[src:cooper-union/125th-street-station-irt-broadway-seventh-avenue-line] The 125th Street station contains two side platforms and three tracks; the center track is not used in regular service.
[src:cooper-union/125th-street-station-irt-broadway-seventh-avenue-line] The station is the only one on the 2,174-foot-long (663 m) Manhattan Valley Viaduct, which carries the Broadway–Seventh Avenue Line across a natural valley surrounding 125th Street.
[src:cooper-union/125th-street-station-irt-broadway-seventh-avenue-line] The platforms contain windscreens and canopies.
[src:cooper-union/125th-street-station-irt-broadway-seventh-avenue-line] The station house beneath the platforms contains exits to 125th Street and Broadway.
[src:cooper-union/125th-street-station-irt-broadway-seventh-avenue-line] The Manhattan Valley Viaduct is a New York City designated landmark and listed on the National Register of Historic Places.
[src:cooper-union/125th-street-station-irt-broadway-seventh-avenue-line] The Manhattan Street station was constructed as part of the IRT's West Side Line (now the Broadway–Seventh Avenue Line).
[src:cooper-union/125th-street-station-irt-broadway-seventh-avenue-line] While most of the original line was designed to be underground, the topography of Manhattanville necessitated the construction of a viaduct between 122nd and 135th Streets.
[src:cooper-union/125th-street-station-irt-broadway-seventh-avenue-line] At the time, the section of 125th Street in West Harlem was known as Manhattan Street; although engineers found that it was technically feasible to dig a tunnel under Manhattan Street, they concluded that such a tunnel would have required a steep grade.
[src:cooper-union/125th-street-station-irt-broadway-seventh-avenue-line] The IRT's engineers originally planned to build a standard elevated structure, similar to those built in other parts of the rapid transit system, with steel columns that supported plate girder spans.
[src:cooper-union/125th-street-station-irt-broadway-seventh-avenue-line] However, this plan would have required rerouting the Third Avenue/125th Street streetcar line, which ran along Manhattan Street.
[src:cooper-union/125th-street-station-irt-broadway-seventh-avenue-line] As such, prior to the start of construction, the plans were changed to a steel viaduct with a double-hinged arch.
[src:cooper-union/125th-street-station-irt-broadway-seventh-avenue-line] The elevated rail section runs from 122nd to 135th Street and was originally called the Manhattan Valley Viaduct.
[src:cooper-union/125th-street-station-irt-broadway-seventh-avenue-line] The name was changed to avoid confusion with the nearby viaduct over Riverside Drive, which also goes by this name.
[src:cooper-union/125th-street-station-irt-broadway-seventh-avenue-line] The aboveground railway has five sections: two embankments at either end, a truss arch over 125th Street, and plate girder bridges connecting the arch with the embankments on either side.
[src:cooper-union/125th-street-station-irt-broadway-seventh-avenue-line] During the planning process, IRT engineers had considered constructing a two-track elevated spur from the viaduct, leading west to a ferry terminal to Fort Lee, New Jersey.
[src:cooper-union/125th-street-station-irt-broadway-seventh-avenue-line] The spur was approved in 1903, and engineers drew up detailed plans for the structure; however, this spur was never built.
[src:cooper-union/125th-street-station-irt-broadway-seventh-avenue-line] Work began on the viaduct over Manhattan Valley on June 1, 1901.
[src:cooper-union/125th-street-station-irt-broadway-seventh-avenue-line] Work on the stone piers and foundations for the viaduct was done by E.
[src:cooper-union/125th-street-station-irt-broadway-seventh-avenue-line] Roberts, while other work was done by Terry & Tench Construction Company.
[src:cooper-union/125th-street-station-irt-broadway-seventh-avenue-line] According to *Tramway and Railway World* magazine, the viaduct was built within two weeks.
[src:cooper-union/125th-street-station-irt-broadway-seventh-avenue-line] Because of delays in constructing the masonry abutment, a portion of the parabolic arch span was built first, followed by the rest of the viaduct.
[src:cooper-union/125th-street-station-irt-broadway-seventh-avenue-line] Normally, the side spans would have been built before the arch was constructed.
[src:cooper-union/125th-street-station-irt-broadway-seventh-avenue-line] The escalators had not been installed by the time the station was scheduled to open, forcing passengers to use temporary stairways.
[src:cooper-union/125th-street-station-irt-broadway-seventh-avenue-line] The 125th Street station opened on October 27, 1904, as the Manhattan Street station, one of the original 28 stations of the New York City Subway from City Hall to 145th Street on the West Side Branch.
[src:cooper-union/125th-street-station-irt-broadway-seventh-avenue-line] The northbound platform at the Manhattan Street station was extended about 98 feet (30 m) to the south, while the southbound platform was not lengthened.
[src:cooper-union/125th-street-station-irt-broadway-seventh-avenue-line] Four stairways at the station were relocated, two stairways were added, and two passageways in the mezzanine were widened during Fiscal Year 1915.
[src:cooper-union/125th-street-station-irt-broadway-seventh-avenue-line] Manhattan Street was renamed 125th Street on April 24, 1921; the original alignment of 125th Street became known as LaSalle Street.
[src:cooper-union/125th-street-station-irt-broadway-seventh-avenue-line] The station was also renamed 125th Street in 1921, following a request from the Harlem Board of Commerce.
[src:cooper-union/125th-street-station-irt-broadway-seventh-avenue-line] A mezzanine below the tracks opened at the station on September 26, 1931, with three new escalators and a new staircase to and from the street.
[src:cooper-union/125th-street-station-irt-broadway-seventh-avenue-line] The span of escalator service was extended from 1 a.m. to 2 a.m. on November 2, 1931.
[src:cooper-union/125th-street-station-irt-broadway-seventh-avenue-line] Platforms at IRT Broadway–Seventh Avenue Line stations between 103rd Street and 238th Street, including those at 125th Street, were lengthened to 514 feet (157 m) in 1948, allowing full ten-car express trains to stop at these stations.
[src:cooper-union/125th-street-station-irt-broadway-seventh-avenue-line] A contract for the platform extensions at 125th Street and five other stations on the line was awarded to the Rao Electrical Equipment Company and the Kaplan Electric Company in June 1946.
[src:cooper-union/125th-street-station-irt-broadway-seventh-avenue-line] The platform extensions at 125th Street opened on June 11, 1948.
[src:cooper-union/125th-street-station-irt-broadway-seventh-avenue-line] On November 24, 1981, the New York City Landmarks Preservation Commission (LPC) designated the Manhattan Valley Viaduct, including the 125th Street station, as a city landmark.
[src:cooper-union/125th-street-station-irt-broadway-seventh-avenue-line] The designation was contentious; the Jewish Theological Seminary argued against the designation because it would prevent the museum from erecting a new structure on or near the site.
[src:cooper-union/125th-street-station-irt-broadway-seventh-avenue-line] The New York City Board of Estimate, which had to ratify the landmark status, upheld the designation in April 1982.
[src:cooper-union/125th-street-station-irt-broadway-seventh-avenue-line] The viaduct and station were added to the National Register of Historic Places in 1983.
[src:cooper-union/125th-street-station-irt-broadway-seventh-avenue-line] In April 1988, the New York City Transit Authority (NYCTA) unveiled plans to speed up service on the Broadway–Seventh Avenue Line through the implementation of a skip-stop service: the 9 train.
[src:cooper-union/125th-street-station-irt-broadway-seventh-avenue-line] As soon as the plan was announced, some local officials were opposed to the change.
[src:cooper-union/125th-street-station-irt-broadway-seventh-avenue-line] Initially, skip-stop service would have been operated north of 116th Street, with 1 trains skipping 125th Street, 157th Street, 207th Street, and 225th Street, and 9 trains skipping 145th Street, 181st Street, Dyckman Street, 215th Street and 238th Street.
[src:cooper-union/125th-street-station-irt-broadway-seventh-avenue-line] However, the plan was changed because riders did not want 125th Street to be a skip-stop station.
[src:cooper-union/125th-street-station-irt-broadway-seventh-avenue-line] When skip-stop service started in 1989, it was only implemented north of 137th Street–City College on weekdays, and 125th Street was served by both the 1 and the 9.
[src:cooper-union/125th-street-station-irt-broadway-seventh-avenue-line] In June 2002, the Metropolitan Transportation Authority (MTA) announced that ten subway stations citywide, including 103rd Street, 110th Street, 116th Street, 125th Street, and 231st Street on the IRT Broadway–Seventh Avenue Line, would receive renovations.
[src:cooper-union/125th-street-station-irt-broadway-seventh-avenue-line] Manhattan Community Board 9 was concerned about preserving the historic nature of the station during its renovation.
[src:cooper-union/125th-street-station-irt-broadway-seventh-avenue-line] Manhattan Community Board 7 got the MTA to agree to maintain the existing design of the wood paneling and windows in the station.
[src:cooper-union/125th-street-station-irt-broadway-seventh-avenue-line] The MTA was expected to decide whether preservation or speed would be prioritized in the station renovation projects by the end of the year.
[src:cooper-union/125th-street-station-irt-broadway-seventh-avenue-line] Between October 5 and November 17, 2003, the downtown platforms at 110th Street and 125th Street were closed to expedite work on their renovations.
[src:cooper-union/125th-street-station-irt-broadway-seventh-avenue-line] In February 2022, local officials requested that the MTA consider adding elevators to the 125th Street station, citing the fact that West Harlem was growing rapidly.
[src:cooper-union/125th-street-station-irt-broadway-seventh-avenue-line] At the time, there was only one fully accessible subway station on the Broadway–Seventh Avenue Line north of 96th Street; that station was 231st Street, several miles north in the Bronx.
[src:cooper-union/125th-street-station-irt-broadway-seventh-avenue-line] Despite calls from local residents, Columbia University, which was developing a 34-story building adjoining the station, originally refused to pay for any of the elevators; it instead offered only to fund the cost of escalators.
[src:cooper-union/125th-street-station-irt-broadway-seventh-avenue-line] In April 2026, Columbia agreed to pay $33 million for new escalators and a street-to-mezzanine elevator.
[src:cooper-union/125th-street-station-irt-broadway-seventh-avenue-line] Under this plan, the MTA would pay for two additional elevators from mezzanine to platform level.
[src:cooper-union/125th-street-station-irt-broadway-seventh-avenue-line] The MTA and Columbia University signed an agreement that May; the project would include the three elevators, new escalators, and repairs to the existing station.
[src:cooper-union/125th-street-station-irt-broadway-seventh-avenue-line] In January 2026, Governor Kathy Hochul announced that she would request funding to extend the Second Avenue Subway along 125th Street.
[src:cooper-union/125th-street-station-irt-broadway-seventh-avenue-line] Although Phase 2 of the line's construction was initially planned to extend only to 125th Street and Lexington Avenue, Hochul's proposal called for additional connections to existing stations at Lenox Avenue, St.
[src:cooper-union/125th-street-station-irt-broadway-seventh-avenue-line] This station was part of the original subway.
[src:cooper-union/125th-street-station-irt-broadway-seventh-avenue-line] It has two side platforms and three tracks; the center track is not used in revenue service.
[src:cooper-union/125th-street-station-irt-broadway-seventh-avenue-line] The station is served by the 1 at all times and is between 137th Street to the north and 116th Street to the south.
[src:cooper-union/125th-street-station-irt-broadway-seventh-avenue-line] Both platforms have beige windscreens and red canopies.
[src:cooper-union/125th-street-station-irt-broadway-seventh-avenue-line] The windscreens have windows and green frames and outlines in the center that were installed in the station's 2003 renovation.
[src:cooper-union/125th-street-station-irt-broadway-seventh-avenue-line] On both ends of the platforms, which are not shaded by canopies, there are green, waist-high, ironwork fences.
[src:cooper-union/125th-street-station-irt-broadway-seventh-avenue-line] The viaduct was originally known as Manhattan Valley Viaduct, a name it shared with the nearby pedestrian and street viaduct over Riverside Drive.
[src:cooper-union/125th-street-station-irt-broadway-seventh-avenue-line] The 125th Street station is the only station on the 2,174-foot-long (663 m) viaduct, which bridges Manhattanville from 122nd to 135th Streets.
[src:cooper-union/125th-street-station-irt-broadway-seventh-avenue-line] The viaduct allows the trains to remain relatively level and avoid steep grades while traversing the valley.
[src:cooper-union/125th-street-station-irt-broadway-seventh-avenue-line] An elevated steel structure with simple steel supports, as used in other parts of the IRT, was not feasible because of the oblique intersection of 125th Street (originally Manhattan Street) and Broadway.
[src:cooper-union/125th-street-station-irt-broadway-seventh-avenue-line] A streetcar ran along Manhattan Street, and the steel support columns would have conflicted with the trolley path.
[src:cooper-union/125th-street-station-irt-broadway-seventh-avenue-line] The choices were a realignment of the street, or a pillarless span over the intersection.
[src:cooper-union/125th-street-station-irt-broadway-seventh-avenue-line] The steel arch across 125th Street is 168.5 feet (51.4 m) long and 54 feet (16 m) high, with foundations descending 30 feet (9.1 m) below street level.
[src:cooper-union/125th-street-station-irt-broadway-seventh-avenue-line] The arch measures 172 feet (52 m) long when measured between the skewbacks on either end.
[src:cooper-union/125th-street-station-irt-broadway-seventh-avenue-line] The arch is composed of three lattice-girder two-hinge ribs, whose centers are spaced 24.5 feet (7.5 m) apart.
[src:cooper-union/125th-street-station-irt-broadway-seventh-avenue-line] Each half rib supports six spandrel posts carrying the tracks.
[src:cooper-union/125th-street-station-irt-broadway-seventh-avenue-line] The chords of the ribs are 6 feet (1.8 m) apart with an H-section.
[src:cooper-union/125th-street-station-irt-broadway-seventh-avenue-line] Each rib was made in 14 sections of equal length.
[src:cooper-union/125th-street-station-irt-broadway-seventh-avenue-line] Most of the remainder of the viaduct is a simple steel structure, similar to other early IRT lines.
[src:cooper-union/125th-street-station-irt-broadway-seventh-avenue-line] Each section measures 46 to 72 feet (14 to 22 m) long with transverse girders 31.33 feet (9.5 m) wide.
[src:cooper-union/125th-street-station-irt-broadway-seventh-avenue-line] Each track was proportioned for a dead load of 330 pounds per foot (490 kg/m) and a live load of 25,000 pounds (11,340 kg) per axle.
[src:cooper-union/125th-street-station-irt-broadway-seventh-avenue-line] The extreme ends of the viaduct contain plate girder bridges across LaSalle Street to the south and 133rd Street to the north.
[src:cooper-union/125th-street-station-irt-broadway-seventh-avenue-line] The span across LaSalle Street measures 86 feet (26 m) long, while that across 133rd Street measures 65 feet (20 m) long.
[src:cooper-union/125th-street-station-irt-broadway-seventh-avenue-line] When the viaduct was completed, it was painted dark green.
[src:cooper-union/125th-street-station-irt-broadway-seventh-avenue-line] The viaduct's southern portal runs from 122nd to LaSalle Streets while the northern portal runs from 133rd to 135th Streets.
[src:cooper-union/125th-street-station-irt-broadway-seventh-avenue-line] These portals are made of brick and stone and are topped by masonry parapets.
[src:cooper-union/125th-street-station-irt-broadway-seventh-avenue-line] Architectural critic Montgomery Schuyler praised the IRT viaduct above 125th Street as "strictly an example of engineering, in which architectural conventions are not recognized at all".
[src:cooper-union/125th-street-station-irt-broadway-seventh-avenue-line] Aside from a complaint that the vertical supports of the arch carried an aesthetic "awkwardness", Schuyler wrote that "it is all the better architecturally" for having been designed for utilitarian purposes.
[src:cooper-union/125th-street-station-irt-broadway-seventh-avenue-line] Architectural writers Norval White and Elliot Willensky wrote in the *AIA Guide to New York City* that the arch was "worthy of Eiffel", a reference to the lattice of the Eiffel Tower.
[src:cooper-union/125th-street-station-irt-broadway-seventh-avenue-line] The 125th Street station has a mezzanine fare control, where a turnstile bank provides access to and from the station.
[src:cooper-union/125th-street-station-irt-broadway-seventh-avenue-line] In the unpaid area, on the west side of the mezzanine, is a token booth and an enclosed passageway, which leads to two escalators going down to the west side of Broadway.
[src:cooper-union/125th-street-station-irt-broadway-seventh-avenue-line] The escalators go in opposite directions: one leads north to 125th Street while the other leads south to Tiemann Place.
[src:cooper-union/125th-street-station-irt-broadway-seventh-avenue-line] On the east side of the station house, another enclosed passageway leads to an escalator facing south and going down to the southeast corner of Broadway and 125th Street.
[src:cooper-union/125th-street-station-irt-broadway-seventh-avenue-line] Adjacent to this passageway is an L-shaped staircase with its upper half directly above Broadway and the lower half beneath the enclosed escalator going to the same corner of the intersection.
[src:cooper-union/125th-street-station-irt-broadway-seventh-avenue-line] When the station opened, drawings show that there were escalators descending to the median of Broadway.
[src:cooper-union/1261-madison-avenue] 1261 Madison Avenue is at the northeast corner of Madison Avenue and 90th Street in the Upper East Side of Manhattan in New York City, New York, US, within the Carnegie Hill neighborhood.
[src:cooper-union/1261-madison-avenue] The building has a frontage, or width, of 62 feet (19 m) along 90th Street to the south, and 100 feet (30 m) along Madison Avenue to the west.
[src:cooper-union/1261-madison-avenue] The building was designed by Buchman & Fox in the Beaux-Arts style for the real-estate developer Gilbert Brown.
[src:cooper-union/1261-madison-avenue] The building measures seven stories high.
[src:cooper-union/1261-madison-avenue] It is surrounded by alleyways to the north and east, making the structure entirely freestanding.
[src:cooper-union/1261-madison-avenue] The outermost bays on Madison Avenue protrude from the rest of the facade.
[src:cooper-union/1261-madison-avenue] On Madison Avenue and 90th Street, the first and second stories have a rusticated limestone facade.
[src:cooper-union/1261-madison-avenue] The first story additionally contains a grand entrance on Madison Avenue, with a short of steps ascending a molded door frame.
[src:cooper-union/1261-madison-avenue] There are rusticated pilasters on either side of steps, along with brackets; a broken pediment above the doorway surrounds a volute with the number "1261" inside it.
[src:cooper-union/1261-madison-avenue] The *AIA Guide to New York City* praised the building's "monumental broken pediment" as the main architectural feature of the building's otherwise nondescript facade.
[src:cooper-union/1261-madison-avenue] Above the broken pediment, on the second floor, is a marble medallion surrounded by a cartouche.
[src:cooper-union/1261-madison-avenue] The third through fifth stories have a smooth limestone facade.
[src:cooper-union/1261-madison-avenue] On these stories, the fourth-story and fifth-story window frames are flanked by quoins (which form a key motif), and the spandrel panels below these stories are carved.
[src:cooper-union/1261-madison-avenue] On the fifth story, the outermost bay on Madison Avenue have cartouches above an arched opening, and there are console brackets above these windows.
[src:cooper-union/1261-madison-avenue] On both elevations of the facade, a cornice runs horizontally above the fifth story, with modillions beneath them and an iron balcony above.
[src:cooper-union/1261-madison-avenue] Within the outer bays on Madison Avenue, the protruding sixth- and seventh-story windows are flanked by double-height pilasters, and there are round pediments above the seventh story.
[src:cooper-union/1261-madison-avenue] On the rest of the facade, the rectangular sixth-story windows are topped by frieze panels, and there is a string course running horizontally above that story.
[src:cooper-union/1261-madison-avenue] The seventh-story windows project from the mansard roof and are topped by curved pediments with various carved ornamentation.
[src:cooper-union/1261-madison-avenue] The construction of the nearby Andrew Carnegie Mansion in the late 1890s spurred large amounts of high-end development in the neighborhood, including several houses and an apartment building at 1291 Madison Avenue.
[src:cooper-union/1261-madison-avenue] In 1923, the developer George Kean bought the building from Bing & Bing.
[src:cooper-union/1261-madison-avenue] Dowling's firm, the City Investing Company, bought the building in 1946; at the time, Dowling also owned the other buildings on the east side of Madison Avenue extending north to 91st Street.
[src:cooper-union/1261-madison-avenue] In 1950, Dowling sold the building to the 1261 Madison Avenue Corporation, a housing cooperative composed of the 16 families who lived there.
[src:cooper-union/cooper-union] The college is divided into three schools: the Irwin S.
[src:cooper-union/cooper-union] Chanin School of Architecture, the School of Art, and the Albert Nerken School of Engineering.
[src:cooper-union/cooper-union] It offers undergraduate and master's degree programs exclusively in the fields of architecture, fine arts (undergraduate only), and engineering, with a shared core curriculum in the humanities and social sciences.
[src:cooper-union/cooper-union] The Cooper Union was one of very few American institutions of higher learning to offer a full-tuition scholarship to every admitted student, a practice it discontinued in 2014, instead offering a half-tuition scholarship to each admitted student.
[src:cooper-union/cooper-union] As of 2024, nearly half of its undergraduate students were attending on a tuition-free basis.
[src:cooper-union/cooper-union] In September 2024 the school announced that for the next four years, all students (including current students) would not pay tuition for their senior year.
[src:cooper-union/cooper-union] The Cooper Union was founded in 1859 by American industrialist Peter Cooper, one of the richest businessmen in the United States.
[src:cooper-union/cooper-union] Cooper was a workingman's son who had less than a year of formal schooling.
[src:cooper-union/cooper-union] Despite this, he designed and built America's first steam railroad engine and made a fortune with a glue factory and iron foundry.
[src:cooper-union/cooper-union] He was a principal investor and first president of the New York, Newfoundland and London Telegraph Company, which laid the first transatlantic telegraph cable, and once ran for President under the Greenback Party, becoming the oldest person ever nominated for the office by a political party.
[src:cooper-union/cooper-union] Cooper's dream was to give talented young people a privilege he had lacked: a good education from an institution which was "open and free to all".
[src:cooper-union/cooper-union] To achieve these goals, Cooper designated the bulk of his wealth to The Cooper Union.
[src:cooper-union/cooper-union] The early institution also had a free reading room open day and night, the first in New York City (predating the New York Public Library system), and a new four-year nighttime engineering college for men and a few women.
[src:cooper-union/cooper-union] In 1883, a five-year curriculum in chemistry was added as an alternative to the applied science (engineering) program.
[src:cooper-union/cooper-union] A daytime engineering college was added in 1902, thanks to funds contributed by Andrew Carnegie.
[src:cooper-union/cooper-union] Initial board members included Daniel F.
[src:cooper-union/cooper-union] Parsons, Horace Greeley and William Cullen Bryant, and those who availed themselves of the institute's courses in its early days included Augustus Saint-Gaudens, Thomas Alva Edison and William Francis Deegan.
[src:cooper-union/cooper-union] The Cooper Union's free classes have evolved into three schools: the School of Art, the Irwin S.
[src:cooper-union/cooper-union] Chanin School of Architecture, and the Albert Nerken School of Engineering.
[src:cooper-union/cooper-union] Since 1859, the Cooper Union has educated thousands of artists, architects, and engineers, many of them leaders in their fields.
[src:cooper-union/cooper-union] After 1864 there were a few attempts to merge Cooper Union and Columbia University, but these were never realized.
[src:cooper-union/cooper-union] The Cooper Hewitt, Smithsonian Design Museum, was founded in 1897 as part of Cooper Union by Sarah, Eleanor, and Amy Hewitt, granddaughters of Peter Cooper.
[src:cooper-union/cooper-union] Cooper Union's Foundation Building is an Italianate brownstone building designed by architect Fred A.
[src:cooper-union/cooper-union] Petersen, one of the founders of the American Institute of Architects.
[src:cooper-union/cooper-union] It was the first structure in New York City to feature rolled-iron I-beams for structural support; Peter Cooper himself invented and produced these beams.
[src:cooper-union/cooper-union] Petersen patented a fire-resistant hollow brick tile he used in the building's construction.
[src:cooper-union/cooper-union] The building was the first in the world to be built with an elevator shaft, because Cooper, in 1853, was confident an elevator would soon be invented.
[src:cooper-union/cooper-union] However, he expected them to be cylindrical, so he designed the shaft in the shape of a circle.
[src:cooper-union/cooper-union] The building was declared a National Historic Landmark in 1961, and a New York City Landmark in 1965, and added to the Historic American Engineering Record in 1971.
[src:cooper-union/cooper-union] On February 27, 1860, the school's Great Hall, located in the basement level of the Foundation Building, became the site of a historic address by Abraham Lincoln.
[src:cooper-union/cooper-union] Widely reported in the press and reprinted throughout the North in pamphlet form, the speech galvanized support for Lincoln and contributed to his gaining the Party's nomination for the presidency.
[src:cooper-union/cooper-union] It is now referred to as the Cooper Union Address.
[src:cooper-union/cooper-union] Since then, the Great Hall has served as a platform for historic addresses by American Presidents Grant, Cleveland, Taft, Theodore Roosevelt, Woodrow Wilson, and Bill Clinton.
[src:cooper-union/cooper-union] Clinton spoke on May 12, 1993, about reducing the federal deficit and again on May 23, 2006, as the Keynote Speaker at The Cooper Union's 147th Commencement, along with Anna Deavere Smith.
[src:cooper-union/cooper-union] He appeared a third time on April 23, 2007, along with Senator Edward Kennedy, Henry Kissinger, Norman Mailer, and others, at the memorial service for historian Arthur M.
[src:cooper-union/cooper-union] Most recently, Barack Obama delivered an economic policy speech at Cooper Union's Great Hall on April 22, 2010.
[src:cooper-union/cooper-union] On September 22, 2014, President of the Palestinian National Authority Mahmoud Abbas delivered his first formal speech in English.
[src:cooper-union/cooper-union] Other historic speakers in the Great Hall have included Frederick Douglass, Susan B.
[src:cooper-union/cooper-union] Anthony, Elizabeth Cady Stanton, and Mark Twain.
[src:cooper-union/cooper-union] When not occupied by external or hosted events, the Great Hall is made accessible to students and faculty for large lectures and recreational activities, including the school's annual Culture Show.
[src:cooper-union/cooper-union] In 1994, the Cooper Union Forum of Public Programs was honored with a Village Award from the Greenwich Village Society for Historic Preservation.
[src:cooper-union/cooper-union] In late 2008, the Great Hall was closed to students and outside events for the first major renovation of the hall since 1978.
[src:cooper-union/cooper-union] The Cooper Union maintains an archive of ephemera and recordings from events that have taken place in the Great Hall through the Voices from the Great Hall Digital Access Project.
[src:cooper-union/cooper-union] The Cooper Union has schools in architecture, fine art, and engineering.
[src:cooper-union/cooper-union] At present, these three fields represent Cooper Union's degree programs.
[src:cooper-union/cooper-union] The Faculty of Humanities and Social Studies provides classes and faculty to all three programs.
[src:cooper-union/cooper-union] In 2002, the school decided to generate revenue by razing its engineering building and having it replaced with a commercial building, and replacing its Hewitt Building with a new building called 41 Cooper Square.
[src:cooper-union/cooper-union] A new classroom, laboratory, and studio facility designed by Thom Mayne replaced the aging Hewitt Academic Building at 41 Cooper Square.
[src:cooper-union/cooper-union] In contrast to the Foundation Building, 41 Cooper Square is of modern, environmentally "green" design, housing nine above-ground floors and two basements.
[src:cooper-union/cooper-union] The structure features unconventional architectural features, including a full-height Grand Atrium, prevalent interior windows, a four-story linear central staircase, and upper-level skyways, which reflect the design intention of inspiring, socially interactive space for students and faculty.
[src:cooper-union/cooper-union] In addition, the building's design allows for up to 75% natural lighting, further reducing energy costs.
[src:cooper-union/cooper-union] In 2010, 41 Cooper Square became the first academic and laboratory structure in New York City to meet Platinum-level LEED standards for energy efficiency.
[src:cooper-union/cooper-union] The building was funded in part by alumni donations, materialized in nameplates and other textual recognition throughout the building.
[src:cooper-union/cooper-union] Primarily designed to house the Cooper Union's School of Engineering and School of Art, the new building's first eight above-ground floors are populated by classrooms, small engineering laboratories, study lounges, art studio space, and faculty offices.
[src:cooper-union/cooper-union] The ninth, top floor is dedicated completely to School of Art studio and classroom space in addition to the art studio spaces located throughout the building.
[src:cooper-union/cooper-union] The lowest basement level consists almost completely of the school's large machine shops and design laboratories, as well as much of the HVAC and supply infrastructure.
[src:cooper-union/cooper-union] The building's first basement level houses primarily the Frederick P.
[src:cooper-union/cooper-union] Rose Auditorium, a 198-capacity lecture hall and event space designed as a smaller, more modern alternative to the Great Hall.
[src:cooper-union/cooper-union] In January 2026, the Cooper Union reached a formal settlement with the U.S.
[src:cooper-union/cooper-union] Department of Education's Office for Civil Rights (OCR) to resolve a federal investigation into allegations of campus antisemitism.
[src:cooper-union/cooper-union] The probe focused on the institution's compliance with Title VI of the Civil Rights Act of 1964, particularly following an October 2023 incident in which Jewish students were required to shelter in a campus library during a pro-Palestinian demonstration.
[src:cooper-union/cooper-union] Under the settlement terms, the college committed to comprehensive institutional reforms, including the revision of its anti-harassment policies, the implementation of enhanced bias-incident reporting protocols, and mandatory training for staff and security personnel.
[src:cooper-union/cooper-union] While the agreement does not constitute an admission of liability by the Cooper Union, the administration has pledged to foster a campus climate that ensures the safety and inclusion of Jewish and Israeli students.
[src:cooper-union/cooper-union] A substantial portion of the annual budget, which supports the full-tuition scholarships in addition to the school's costs, is generated through revenues from real estate.
[src:cooper-union/cooper-union] The land under the Chrysler Building is owned by the endowment, and as of 2009, Cooper Union received $7 million per year from this parcel.
[src:cooper-union/cooper-union] Further, under a very unusual arrangement, New York City real-estate taxes assessed against the Chrysler lease, held by Aby Rosen, are paid to Cooper Union, not the city.
[src:cooper-union/cooper-union] This arrangement would be voided if Cooper Union sold the real estate.
[src:cooper-union/cooper-union] In 2006, Tishman Speyer signed a deal with the school to pay rent that has escalated to $32.5 million in 2018.
[src:cooper-union/cooper-union] Around October 29, 2011, rumors circulated the school was in serious financial trouble.
[src:cooper-union/cooper-union] On October 31, a series of open forums were held with students, faculty, and alumni to address a financial crisis.
[src:cooper-union/cooper-union] Current and past students voiced opposition to charging tuition.
[src:cooper-union/cooper-union] The then-president of the school, Jamshed Bharucha, indicated depletion of the school's endowment required additional sources of funding.
[src:cooper-union/cooper-union] In 2012, the college announced approval from its board of trustees to attempt to establish a new tuition-based cross-disciplinary graduate program, expand its fee-based continuing education programs, and impose tuition on some students in its existing graduate programs.
[src:cooper-union/cooper-union] In December 2012, as a protest against the possibility of undergraduate tuition being charged, 11 students occupied a suite in the Foundation Building for a week.
[src:cooper-union/cooper-union] Charging high tuition was complicated by the school's lack of customary amenities offered by other high-tuition schools.
[src:cooper-union/cooper-union] The college ended its free tuition policy for undergraduates in 2014, but offers need-based tuition remission to incoming undergraduates on a sliding scale.
[src:cooper-union/cooper-union] On May 8, 2013, a group of students occupied President Bharucha's office in protest over news reports about ending free tuition.
[src:cooper-union/cooper-union] The administration, board of trustees, and those members of the Cooper Union community who had been occupying the Office of the President since early May reached an agreement that ended the occupation on July 12.
[src:cooper-union/cooper-union] On September 1, 2015, the school and the CSCU announced the CSCU's lawsuit against the school's administration was resolved in the form of a consent decree signed by Cooper Union, then-New York State's Attorney General Eric Schneiderman, and the CSCU.
[src:cooper-union/cooper-union] The decree includes provisions for returning to a sustainable, tuition-free policy, increased board transparency, additional student, faculty and alumni trustees, an independent financial monitor appointed by the Attorney General, and a search committee to identify the next full-term president.
[src:cooper-union/cooper-union] On January 15, 2018, the Free Education Committee (FEC) of the school's Board of Trustees released their recommended plan to return to full-tuition scholarships for undergraduates only by the academic year starting in the fall of 2028.
[src:cooper-union/cooper-union] In March 2018, the board released its approved, updated version with the same milestone.
[src:cooper-union/cooper-union] In 2024, the school announced that approximately 83% of undergraduate tuition costs would be covered by scholarships in the 2024–2025 academic year and that they were proceeding as planned towards their goal of 100% coverage in the 2029 fiscal year.
[src:cooper-union/cooper-union] Admission to Cooper Union is highly competitive, with an acceptance rate of 12% across the three schools.
[src:cooper-union/cooper-union] The Cooper Union's School of Engineering is named in honor of Albert Nerken, a chemical engineering alumnus of the school.
[src:cooper-union/cooper-union] Its enrollment includes about 550 students, and is the largest of the three schools by a significant margin.
[src:cooper-union/cooper-union] The school offers ABET-accredited Bachelor of Engineering (BE) degree programs in core engineering fields and an interdisciplinary Bachelor of Science in Engineering (BSE) degree.
[src:cooper-union/cooper-union] Opportunities are also available for engineering students to pursue minors in bioengineering, chemistry, computer science, humanities and social sciences, and mathematics.
[src:cooper-union/cooper-union] Specialized facilities for teaching and research include the Maurice Kanbar Center for Biomedical Engineering established in 2002 and the interdisciplinary Maker Space Lab, established in 2020 for the use of engineering, art, and architecture students.
[src:cooper-union/cooper-union] The School of Engineering offers master's degrees in chemical, civil, electrical, or mechanical engineering.
[src:cooper-union/cooper-union] Cooper Union undergraduate engineering students may earn a bachelor's degree and a master's degree in as little as five years.
[src:cooper-union/cooper-union] Consisting of roughly 200 students and 70 faculty members, the Cooper Union School of Art offers a Bachelor of Fine Arts (BFA) degree and a Certificate of Fine Arts.
[src:cooper-union/cooper-union] As a member school of AICAD, School of Art students may participate in exchange programs with the other colleges in the association, including California Institute of the Arts and Otis College of Art and Design.
[src:cooper-union/cooper-union] The curriculum place heavy emphasis on each student's creative and imaginative abilities, rather than technical precision in a specific medium.
[src:cooper-union/cooper-union] Located in both public spaces and specialized rooms, Cooper Union's galleries provide space for installations and showcases by students, faculty, and guest artists.
[src:cooper-union/cooper-union] In addition, numerous smaller exhibition spaces exist throughout both buildings on campus.
[src:cooper-union/cooper-union] Larger spaces on the upper floors of the Foundation Building are used primarily for interdisciplinary exhibitions with the School of Architecture.
[src:cooper-union/cooper-union] For presentations of video and digital media, the Great Hall and 41 Cooper Square's Rose Auditorium are used.
[src:cooper-union/cooper-union] Chanin School of Architecture at The Cooper Union offers a five-year NAAB accredited program established by John Hejduk.
[src:cooper-union/cooper-union] The faculty includes architects, design and construction managers such as Peter Eisenman, Samuel Anderson, Nader Tehrani, and Diana Agrest.
[src:cooper-union/cooper-union] Former faculty members include the architects Michael Webb, Peter Eisenman, Raimund Abraham, Lebbeus Woods, Diane Lewis and John Hejduk.
[src:cooper-union/cooper-union] The post-professional degree program in architecture was launched in 2009.
[src:cooper-union/cooper-union] Concentrations in one or a combination of three areas are offered: theory, history and criticism of architecture, urban studies and technologies.
[src:cooper-union/cooper-union] Cooper Union has developed an athletic program which fields teams in basketball, volleyball, and soccer.
[src:cooper-union/cooper-union] The institution has also had 40 Fulbright Scholars since 2001 and 13 National Science Foundation Graduate Research Fellowships since 2004.
[src:cooper-union/cooper-union] Cooper Union has been used as a filming location for movie and television.
[src:cooper-union/cooper-union] *Winter's Tale* (2014) was filmed at Cooper's foundation building to fit the novel's early 1900 setting.
[src:cooper-union/cooper-union] Additionally, 41 Cooper Square was frequently shown in episodes of the television series *Instinct*, wherein it was depicted as the New York City Police Department's 11th Precinct.
